fields.description: A derivational unit that derives intransitive stems from adjectives, with the meaning of becoming or taking on the quality of the adjective.
fields.label: Versive

fields.description: An OrthographicPhrase is a sequence of orthographic words.
fields.label: OrthographicPhrase

fields.description:
Associated with transitivity, when the action is performed by an agent (subject) on another participant (object), or with intransitivity [McIntosh 1984, 108]. Refers to the category of underived verb forms associated with the basic diathesis: Diathesis=D0:(X=SUBabs/nom) (Y=DIROBacc)
[Shibatani 1995, 7]
fields.label: ActiveVoice

fields.description: no documentation yet
fields.label: Proverb

fields.description: [Need comment]
fields.label: Approximant

fields.description: GeneticTaxon is the class of all taxons whose members are based on genetic relatedness.
fields.label: GeneticTaxon

fields.description: A quantifier is a determiner that expresses a referent's definite or indefinite  number or amount. A quantifier functions as a modifier of a noun, or a pronoun [Crystal 1997, 317].
fields.label: Quantifier

fields.description: PartitiveCase expresses the partial nature of the referent of the noun it marks, as opposed to expressing the whole unit or class of which the referent is a part. This case may be found in items such as the following: existential clauses, nouns that are accompanied by numerals or units of measure, or predications of material from which something is made. It often has a meaning similar to the English word 'some' [Pei and Gaynor 1954, 161; Richards, Platt, and Weber 1985, 208; Quirk, et al. 1985, 249; Sebeok 1946, 1214].
fields.label: PartitiveCase

fields.description: Action denotes physical/mental disposition of subject. [Siewierska 1988,257]
fields.label: DeponentMiddleVoice

fields.description: Predicator is the class of syntactic words that are fundamentally relation inducing. That is, predicators license argument structure [Anderson 1997, 14]. fields.label: Predicator

fields.label: GrammarUnit

fields.description:
A value of Tense Property assigned to the designated element in the clause when the meaning selected for the clause is that intended to locate the event spoken about as anterior to the deictic centre of the utterance. Most commonly, this tense meaning is referred to as 'past', because in absolute tense systems the deictic centre is the moment of speech. However, in relative tense systems, where the deictic centre can be moved to any point on the time line, it is more appropriate to refer to this temporal relation as 'anterior'.

The anterior temporal relation may obtain either in 'simple' or 'perfect' contexts. Modelling of this distinction originates from [Reichenbach 1947], who suggested using a third point in time, 'reference point', to capture all possible tense distinctions. In all 'simple' temporal relations, the reference point coincides with the location of the event spoken about. 'Perfect' tense meanings are created when the reference point is separated and moved away from the event time, thus altering the viewing of the temporal location of the event even though the event's actual location with respect to the deictic centre remains the same. 

A common instance of an anterior temporal relationship obtaining in a 'perfect' context occurs when the reference point is moved away from the event time and located instead at the moment of speech. The event time is still anterior to the moment of speech, but it is viewed against a stretch of time which began at the event and continues up to the moment of speech --- e.g. the English I have read this book, I have seen John --- hence the interpretation that the event has an effect or is in some way still relevant at the moment of speech. In some languages (e.g. English) this tense meaning is labelled as (one of the uses of the) Present Perfect, in others (e.g. Polish) this meaning may be collapsed with the 'simple' anterior meaning and labelled simply as Past.

Typically, for a tense value to be labelled as Past Tense, the tense meaning has to minimally express the anterior temporal relationship, although it may additionally express other temporal relationships or aspectual and/or modal meanings. For example, when the usage of the Past Tense value is restricted to a semantically defined domain, it is conventional to add a further qualification to the label of the Past Tense value (e.g. Past Imperfective --- when the anterior temporal relationship is necessarily combined with an aspectual meaning of the Imperfective Aspect value, and grammaticalised as a single TAM category in the language).
fields.label: PastTense

fields.label: PulmonicProperty

fields.description: LativeCase expresses 'motion up to the location of,' or 'as far as' the referent of the noun it marks [Pei and Gaynor 1954, 121].
fields.label: LativeCase

fields.description: AblativeCase expresses that  the referent of the noun it marks is the location from which another referent is moving. It has the meaning 'from'.
fields.label: AblativeCase

fields.description: ContablativeCase expresses that  the referent of the noun it marks is the location 'from near' which another referent is moving. It has the meaning 'from near'.
fields.label: ContablativeCase

fields.description: A Proadjective is a proForm that substitutes for an adjective or adjective phrase.
fields.label: Proadjective

fields.description: EndangermentTaxon is a class of taxons based on the robustness of its members. Endangerment is based on a number of criteria including the number of speakers, the average age of the native-speaker population, etc.
fields.label: EndangermentTaxon

fields.description: In a given language, the system according to which feature values (of a particular feature) are assigned inherently to elements, based on the elements' inherent formal or semantic properties.
fields.label: FeatureAssignmentSystem

fields.description: Clause is the class of constructions that form minimal sentential units. They must  include a predicate, all arguments of the predicate, and all modifiers of the predicate and the arguments.
fields.label: Clause

fields.description: A transitive verb is a verb that takes a direct object, and describes a relation between two participants [Crystal 1997,397; Payne 1997,171].
fields.label: TransitiveVerb

fields.description: In general, positive polarity refers to an assertion that contains no marker of negation [Crystal 1980,  299].
fields.label: PositivePolarity

fields.description:
A value of Aspect Property assigned to the designated element in the clause when the meaning selected for the clause is that which indicates that the event spoken about is to be looked at from inside, from within its temporal boundaries; imperfective aspect is crucially concerned with the internal temporal structure of the event [Comrie 1976, 16ff].

Typically, for an aspect value to be labelled as Imperfective, the aspectual meaning has to minimally express the imperfective viewpoint, although it may additionally express other temporal, aspectual, or modal meanings, or actionality distinctions.

Imperfective aspectual meaning can be further subdivided into two types: habitual meaning and continuous meaning. These two aspectual meanings may or may not be grammaticalised as separate aspect values.
fields.label: ImperfectiveAspect

fields.description: [Need comment]
fields.label: Mid

fields.description: SmallPaucal is a number property that occurs in a number system together with LargePlural, referring to a very small number of individuals. It core:entails Paucal and is entailed by both Singular and Dual.
fields.label: SmallPaucalNumber

fields.description: A SimpleSpecification is a kind of FeatureSpecification whose value must be a simple linguistic attribute [Maxwell, Simons, and Hayashi 2000].
fields.label: SimpleSpecification

fields.description: PossessedCase is used to mark the noun whose referent is possessed by the referent of another noun.
fields.label: PossessedCase

fields.description: suggested at E-MELD  (no documentation yet)
fields.label: VerbalAdjective

fields.description: SubessiveCase expresses that  the referent of the noun it marks is the location under which another referent exists. It has the meaning of 'under' or 'beneath'.
fields.label: SubessiveCase

fields.description: NumberProperty is the class of properties that concern the grammatical encoding of quantity. It is often found on nouns, pronouns, and verbs and expresses count distinctions--such as 'one' or 'more than one'. The count distinctions typically, but not always, correspond to the actual count of the referents of the marked noun or Pronoun [Crystal 1980, 245; Hartmann and Stork 1972, 155].
fields.label: NumberProperty

fields.description: SyntacticArgument is the class of syntactic words that are fundamentally referable and  non-relational [Anderson 1997, 15]. Proper names are the quintessential arguments, though pronouns and nouns possess  argument properties.
fields.label: SyntacticArgument

fields.description: no documentation yet
fields.label: Participle

fields.description: An interjection is a part of speech, typically brief in form, such as one syllable or word, whose members are used most often as exclamations or parts of an exclamation. An interjection, typically expressing an emotional reaction, often with respect to an accompanying sentence, is not syntactically related to other accompanying expressions, and may include a combination of sounds not otherwise found in the language [Crystal 1997,200].
fields.label: Interjection

fields.description: Property of sounds characterized by focusing on the active articulator.
fields.label: SupraLaryngealProperty

fields.description: Characterizing sounds produced by the tip of the tongue [Ladefoged 1997, 596].
fields.label: Apical

fields.description: Functor is the class of syntactic word whose members are neither relation- nor argument-like non-relational [Anderson 1997, 20]. Typical functors include adpositions, subordinators, and complementizers.
fields.label: Functor

fields.description: Locates the situation in question prior to a reference time in the past before the time of the speaking event. This is also known as the PluperfectTense [Comrie 1985, 125].
fields.label: PastInPastTense

fields.description:
Associated with actions performed on the subject by an unspecified agent.
[McIntosh 1984,108] Refers to the category of verb forms, typically identifies with a specific morphological marking, that encode the derived diatheses in which the agent role is not linked with a subject noun phrase: Diatheis: D1=(X=AgOb)(Y+SUBabs/nom) [Shibatani 1995,7]
fields.label: PassiveVoice

fields.description: InceptiveAspect, also called the ingressive, encodes the beginning portion of some event [Bybee 1985, 147, 149; Payne 1997, 240; Bhat 1999,176].
fields.label: InceptiveAspect

fields.description: [Need comment]
fields.label: TerminativeCase

fields.description: If the agent outranks the patient on the relevant generic topic hierarchy, the direct-active clause is used.  If the relevant norm is reversed and the patient outranks the agent on the relevant hierarchy, the inverse clause is used. [Givon 1994,23]
fields.label: SemanticInverseVoice

fields.description: PostHodiernalFutureTense locates the situation in question after the span that is culturally defined as 'today' [Bybee, Perkins, and Pagliuca 1994, 247].
fields.label: PostHodiernalFutureTense

fields.description: A subclass of place Properties roughly referring to positions inside the mouth [Ladefoged 1997, 606].
fields.label: BuccalProperty

fields.description: The simultaneous temporal relation may obtain either in 'simple' or 'perfect' contexts.  Modelling of this distinction originates from [Reichenbach  1947], who suggested using a third point in time, 'reference point', to capture all possible tense distinctions. In all 'simple' temporal relations, the reference point coincides with the location of the event spoken about.
fields.label: SimplePresentTense

fields.description: suggested at E-MELD  (no documentation yet)
fields.label: SuperlativeAdjective

fields.description: IndirectEvidentiality, also called reported, encodes the fact that the speaker came to believe the content of the expression from a source other than by experiencing the situation directly [Palmer 2001, 40].
fields.label: IndirectEvidentiality

fields.description: ContlativeCase expresses that  the referent of the noun it marks is the location in the vicinity of which another referent is moving. It has the meaning 'in the vicinity of'.
fields.label: ContlativeCase

fields.description: Third Person is a person property that refers to the non-participant (other than the speaker and the addressee) [Crystal 1997, 285].
fields.label: ThirdPerson

fields.description: AuditoryEvidentiality encodes the fact that the speaker came to believe the content of the expression through direct auditory experience; they heard it. This does not include spoken reported accounts, but only direct sensory evidence, such as the situation of 'hearing a tree fall' [Palmer 2001, 38].
fields.label: AuditoryEvidentiality

fields.description: ObliqueCase
fields.label: ObliqueCase

fields.description: The class of all kinds of units, defined according to the particular level of linguistic analysis.
fields.label: LinguisticUnit

fields.description: HesternalPastTense locates the situation in question somewhere in the span beginning with the period defined culturally as 'yesterday' and extends back through some period that is considered nonremote [Comrie 1985,87-88; Dahl 1985,126].
fields.label: HesternalPastTense

fields.description: RemotePastTense locates the situation in question prior to the present moment, usually more than a few days ago [Dahl 1985,121; Comrie 1985,88]. Subsumes notion of PreHesternalPast tense, which locates the situation in question before that of an opposing hesternal past tense. [Bybee, Perkins, Pagliuca 1994, 98].
fields.label: RemotePastTense

fields.description: StillPresentTense is similar to PresentTense but carries the presupposition that an event or state held before the moment of utterance. In positive declarative clauses, still present tense asserts that the event or state holds at the moment of utterance [Comrie 1985, 54].
fields.label: StillTense

fields.description: A personal pronoun is a pronoun that expresses a distinction of person deixis.
fields.label: PersonalPronoun

fields.description: ExtinctVariety is the class of human language varieties that no longer have native speakers, e.g., Frankish or Mozarabic.
fields.label: ExtinctVariety

fields.description: AdessiveCase expresses that  the referent of the noun it marks is the location near/at which another referent exists. It has the meaning of 'at' or 'near' [Crystal 1997, 8].
fields.label: AdessiveCase

fields.description: The class of properties used to describe speech sounds. The properties given here are more or less taken directly from Ladefoged's later works, in particular, the taxonomies of [Ladefoged  1997].
fields.label: PhoneticProperty

fields.description: Any entity that does not occupy a position in space and  time. See SUMO for a detailed explanation.
fields.label: Abstract

fields.description: A part of speech derived from a verb and used as a noun, usually restricted to non-finite forms of the verb [Crystal 1997, 279].
fields.label: Gerund

fields.description: A passive in Irish  in which the preposition "at" is used, and a semantic meaning of progressive tense is found [Noonan 1994,280]
fields.label: ProgressivePassiveVoice

fields.description:
A value of Aspect Property assigned to the designated element in the clause when the meaning selected for the clause is that which indicates that the situation spoken about has internal temporal structure, but the situation cannot be regarded as habitual (i.e. it cannot be regarded as a characteristic feature of a whole period). Hence, continuousness can be defined negatively as imperfectivity that is not habituality [Comrie 1976, 26-32], and it can be regarded as a sub-type of imperfectivity.

Typically, for an aspect value to be labelled as Continuous, the aspectual meaning has to minimally express continuousness, although it may additionally express other temporal, aspectual, or modal meanings, or actionality distinctions.

Continuous aspectual meaning can be further subdivided into two types: progressive meaning and nonprogressive meaning. These two aspectual meanings may or may not be grammaticalised as separate aspect values.
fields.label: ContinuousAspect

fields.description: Group is the class of syntactic constructions intermediate between the level of word and phrase.
fields.label: Group

fields.description: [Need comment]
fields.label: PlusClick

fields.description: A Determiner is a part of speech whose members belong to a class of noun modifiers and express the reference, including  quantity, of a noun [Crystal 1997,112].
fields.label: Determiner

fields.description: The anterior temporal relation may obtain either in 'simple' or 'perfect' contexts. Modelling of this distinction originates from [Reichenbach  1947], who suggested using a third point in time, 'reference point', to capture all possible tense distinctions. In all 'simple' temporal relations, the reference point coincides with the location of the event spoken about.
fields.label: SimplePastTense

fields.description: A ProForm is a partOfSpeech whose members usually substitute for other constituents, including phrases, clauses, or sentences, and whose meaning is recoverable from the linguistic or extralinguistic context [Schachter 1985,24-25; Crystal 1997,310].
fields.label: ProForm

fields.description: [Need a definition.]
fields.label: AirstreamProperty

fields.description: EpistemicModality indicates that a state of affairs is known to be possible or certain (necessary).
fields.label: EpistemicModality

fields.description: PlusNasal
fields.label: PlusNasal

fields.description: LanguageSubfamily is a grouping of languages defined more narrowly than a LanguageFamily. In a given Subfamily, all languages are genetically related and are instances of the same LanguageFamily. For there to be a subfamily, there must be a family.
fields.label: LanguageSubfamily

fields.description: If the agent is more topical than the patient, the direct-active clause is used.  If norm is reversed and the patient is more topical, the inverse clause is used. [Givon 1994,23]
fields.label: PragmaticInverseVoice

fields.description: [Bybee, Perkins and Pagliuca, 1984]
fields.label: CompletiveAspect

fields.description: [No definition yet.]
fields.label: Toneme

fields.description: AbessiveCase expresses the lack or absence of the referent of the noun it marks. It has the meaning of the English preposition 'without' [Pei and Gaynor 1954, 3, 35].
fields.label: AbessiveCase

fields.description: IndicativeMood indicates that the speaker believes the expression to be true.
fields.label: IndicativeMood

fields.description: IntertranslativeCase expresses the notion of something moving along a trajectory between the referent of the noun it marks. It has the meaning 'along the in between'.
fields.label: IntertranslativeCase

fields.description: A specification of a view of a particular item.
fields.label: Viewer

fields.description: Defines the structure of a DataSet or slice
fields.label: Data structure definition

fields.description: Superclass of all coded ComponentProperties
fields.label: Coded property

fields.description: Abstract class of things which reference one or more ComponentProperties
fields.label: Component set

fields.description: The class of components which represent the dimensions of the cube
fields.label: Dimension property

fields.description: Abstract super-property of all properties representing dimensions, attributes or measures
fields.label: Component property (abstract)

fields.description: Used to define properties of a component (attribute, dimension etc) which are specific to its usage in a DSD.
fields.label: Component specification

fields.description: Denotes a subset of a DataSet defined by fixing a subset of the dimensional values, component properties on the Slice
fields.label: Slice

fields.description: Abstract superclass for everything that can have attributes and dimensions
fields.label: Attachable (abstract)

fields.description: A single observation in the cube, may have one or more associated measured values
fields.label: Observation

fields.description: Represents a collection of observations, possibly organized into various slices, conforming to some common dimensional structure.
fields.label: Data set

fields.description: The class of components which represent attributes of observations in the cube, e.g. unit of measurement
fields.label: Attribute property

fields.description: Denotes a subset of the component properties of a DataSet which are fixed in the corresponding slices
fields.label: Slice key

fields.description: The class of components which represent the measured value of the phenomenon being observed
fields.label: Measure property

fields.description: concept for a dimension or attribute that plays the role of the DataAttribute subject to whom the data refers (e.g. the reporting agent for primary reporting, the country for secondary reporting)
fields.label: Entity property

fields.description: concept for a dimension or attribute that plays the role of frequency
fields.label: Frequency property

fields.description: concept for a dimension or attribute that plays the role of an identifier where the identifier is taken from a known system of counts (e.g. the Nth current dataset update for a given day)
fields.label: Count property

fields.description: concept for a dimension or attribute that plays the role of an identifier which is taken from a known scheme of identifiers.
fields.label: Identity property

fields.description: concept for a dimension that plays the role of identifying a type of measure
fields.label: Measure type property

fields.description: concept for a dimension or attribute that plays the role of a date/time identifier in the KeyFamily which is not related to the time of the observation

fields.description: concept for a dimension that specifies the time of the observation of the primaryMeasure

fields.description: Abstract superclass of classes denoting statistical roles which be played by concepts

fields.description: concept for a measure that plays the role of the observation in a time series

fields.description: A specialization of qb:DataStructureDefinition which additional constraints: if there are multiple measures then a MeasureDimensionProperty must be included in the DSD
fields.label: Data Structure Definition

fields.description: Denotes an SDMX concept, used in the particular SDMX terminological sense, which is in principle narrower than skos:Concept
fields.label: concept

fields.description:
A collection of
            one or more media recordings.
fields.label: media:Collection

fields.description: A recording of an item of interest in any form.
fields.label: media:Recording

fields.description: A Tag consists of an arbitrary text label. Note that tags with the same label are NOT merged in the ontology.
fields.label: Tag

fields.description: A tagging links a resource to a user account and one or more tags.
fields.label: Tagging

fields.description: An automatic tag is a tag that is automatically associated with a resource (e.g. by a tagging system), i.e. it is not entered by a human being.
fields.label: Automatic Tag

fields.description: A private tagging is a tagging that is only visible to its creator (unless the creator has not granted access to others via muto:grantAccess). Every tagging that is not an instance of muto:PrivateTagging is public by default.
fields.label: Private Tagging

fields.description: An image. Any PictorialElement that is considered to be a complete image. Typically the main subject of an ImageSnippets description will be in this class. An image can be a visualPartOf another image.
fields.label: Image

fields.description:
Any visual entity; any graphical item, part, or visual property of an image or part of an image, including the image itself. Examples include lines, areas, colors and textures. Pictorial elements may have arbitrarily complex shapes and may be implicit, e.g. lines of perspective or outlined white spaces. Rectangular regions of an image are pictorial elements, and the entire image is also. Thus, Image is a subclass of PictorialElement. 
PictorialElements may be included in one another, giving a simple mereology of visual forms, with the property visualPartOf.
Non-visual properties such as date or manner of creation are not considered to be PictorialElements. A property or aspect of an image can be considered to be a PictorialElment when it can be apprehended by vision alone.
fields.label: Pictorial Element

fields.description: Use this type when nothing else fits.
fields.label: Misc

fields.description: A work that is printed and bound, but without a named publisher or sponsoring institution.
fields.label: Booklet

fields.description: A report published by a school or other institution, usually numbered within a series.
fields.label: Techreport

fields.description: An article in a conference proceedings.
fields.label: Inproceedings

fields.description: A document having an author and title, but not formally published.
fields.label: Unpublished

fields.description: A part of a book, which may be a chapter (or section or whatever) and/or a range of pages.
fields.label: Inbook

fields.description: A PhD thesis.
fields.label: Phdthesis

fields.description: A Master's thesis.
fields.label: Mastersthesis

fields.description: A book with an explicit publisher.
fields.label: Book

fields.description: Base class for all entries
fields.label: Entry

fields.description: The same as INPROCEEDINGS, included for Scribe compatibility.
fields.label: Conference

fields.description: A part of a book having its own title.
fields.label: Incollection

fields.description: Technical documentation.
fields.label: Manual

fields.description: The proceedings of a conference.
fields.label: Proceedings

fields.description: An article from a journal or magazine.
fields.label: Article

fields.description: ひとつの例を表すクラス
fields.label: Example

fields.description: Process refers to an action or series of actions performed on or caused by artifacts, and resulting in new artifacts.
fields.label: Process

fields.description: Agent is a contextual entity acting as a catalyst of a process, enabling, facilitating, controlling, or affecting its execution.
fields.label: Agent

fields.description: Artifact is a general concept that represents immutable piece of state, which may have a physical embodiment in a physical object, or a digital representation in a computer system.
fields.label: Artifact

fields.description: A class for representing an entry from a playlist. One PlaylistEntry instance is connected to one Song instance and one Playlist instance. It contains information about the 'position' of the Song in the Playlist, for the specific 'week' of the 'year'. It also contains an URL of a 'photo' for the playlist entry.
fields.label: Playlist Entry

fields.description: A class for representing a playlist. One Playlist instance is connected to one or more PlaylistEntry instances. It contains the name of the playlist and the name of the radio station.
fields.label: Playlist

fields.description: A class for representing a song. One Song instance is connected to one or more PlaylistEntry instances. It contains the name of the song and the name of the artist. It can also contain external links to mo:Track and/or mo:MusicArtist instances, for creating Linked Data.
fields.label: Song

fields.description: Execution is a general class that represents completed executions of actions or processes. An execution is usually performed by an actor (see the class Actor) and an execution, in most cases, yielded an artifact (see the class Artifact).
fields.label: Execution

fields.description: Document is a general class that represents a Web representation (i.e. a document) with which a data item has been retrieved from the Web.
fields.label: Web Document

fields.description: DataCreation is a class that represents the completed creation of a data item.
fields.label: Data Creation

fields.description: NonHumanActor is a general class that represents actors who are not social beings.
fields.label: Non-Human Actor

fields.description: DataItem is a general class that represents data items of any kind.
fields.label: Data Item

fields.description: Artifact is a general class that represents artifacts which can be used during the execution (see the class Execution) of an action or a process and which can also be the result of such an execution.
fields.label: Artifact

fields.description: CreationGuideline is a class that represents a guideline used to guide the execution of a data creation. Examples for creation guidelines are transformation rules, mapping definitions, entailment rules, and database queries.
fields.label: Creation Guideline

fields.description: HumanActor is a general class that represents actors who are social beings such as persons, organizations, companies.
fields.label: Human Actor

fields.description: DataProvidingService is a class that represents a non-human actor - usually a Web service or a server - that processes data access requests and actually sends the requested Web representations (i.e. prv:Document) over the Web.
fields.label: Data Providing Service

fields.description: DataAccess is a class that represents the completed execution of accessing a data item on the Web.
fields.label: Data Access

fields.description: Actor is a general class that represents actors which usually performed the execution (see the class Execution) of an action or a process.
fields.label: Actor

fields.description: DataPublisher is a class that represents entities such as persons, groups, or organizations who use a data providing service (see class prv:DataProvidingService) to publish data on the Web.
fields.label: Data Publisher

fields.description: A QueryTemplate is a query that contains placeholders which are replaced by actual data to create an executable query.
fields.label: Query Template

fields.description: TriplifyMapping is a concept that represents the mapping defined in a Triplify configuration file.
fields.label: Triplify Mapping

fields.description: DataCreatingService is a concept that represents a software service which performed the creation of a data item. Examples for data creating services are reasoners, query engines, and workflow engines.
fields.label: Data Creating Service

fields.description: QueryResult is the result of a query execution.
fields.label: Query Result

fields.description: DataCreatingDevice is a concept that represents a device which performed the creation of a data item. Examples for data creating devices are sensors.
fields.label: Data Creating Device

fields.description: DataCreator is a concept that represents an agent which performed the creation of a data item.
fields.label: Data Creator

fields.description: DataCreatingEntity is a concept that represents a human agent who performed the creation of a data item, either directly or by being responsible for a non-human data creator (see the concepts prvTypes:DataCreatingService and prvTypes:DataCreatingDevice).
fields.label: Data Creating Entity

fields.description: An HTTPBasedDataAccess represents the completed execution of accessing a data item using the HTTP protocol.
fields.label: HTTP-based Data Access

fields.description: Measurement is a concept that represents the execution of a measurement.
fields.label: Measurement

fields.description: DataAccessor is a concept that represents a system (i.e. a non-human agent) which performed the data access in order to retrieve an information resource from the Web.
fields.label: Data Accessor

fields.description: Workflows that bring together multiple access or analysis activities usually contain steps for format transformations. These steps preserve the content of the inputs while converting its representation format. An example would be a converter from CSV to VOTable format in the astronomy domain, a converter from FASTA to Swiss-Prott sequence in biology, or an Arff formating component for Weka in the text analysis domain.
fields.label: Format transformation

fields.description: Data preparation motif that refers to the step or set of steps dedicated to generate an aggregation of multiple parameters and scripts for tools and external services. For example, the generation of queries for input retrieval through an aggregation of multiple parameters, the generation of scripts to be executed in further steps, etc.
fields.label: Input augmentation

fields.description: A data operation motif describes the data manipulation and/or transformation carried out by a step in the workflow, a collection of steps in the workflow or a sub-workflow.
fields.label: Data operation motif

fields.description: Inter-workflow motif used to characterize the workflows that perform an atomic unit of functionality, which effectively requires no sub-workflow usage. Typically these workflows are designed to be included in other workflows. Atomic workflows are the main mechanism of modularizing functionality within scientific workflows.
fields.label: Atomic workflow

fields.description: Workflow motif that describes a step or a series of steps within a single workflow.
fields.label: Intra-workflow motif

fields.description: Motif that describes how a data operation motif is realized (i.e., implemented) within a workflow. For example, a visualization step (data operation motif) can be realized in different ways: via a stateful multi-step invocation, through a single stateless invocation (depending on the environmental constraints and nature of the services), or via a sub-workflow.
fields.label: Workflow motif

fields.description: Intra-workflow motif that requires a step in the workflow for performing a service call or tool invocation. All the steps of a workflow are by default stateless (synchronous) invocations unless they are explicitly declared to be stateful.
fields.label: Stateless (synchronous) invocation

fields.description: Data preparation motif that refers to the step or steps in the workflow separating an input into different outputs. For example, splitting a dataset in three different subsets to be processed in parallel in a workflow.
fields.label: Split

fields.description: Inter-workflow motif referring to all those workflows that have one or more sub-workflows included in them (when these sub-workflows overlap they offer different views of the global workflow).
fields.label: Composite workflow

fields.description: Workflows exploit heterogeneous data sources, remote databases, repositories and other web resources mostly exposed via SOAP or REST services. Scientific data deposited in these repositories are retrieved through query and retrieval steps inside workflows. The data retrieval motif identifies those tasks within the workflow which are responsible for retrieving data from external sources into the workflow environment.
fields.label: Data retrieval

fields.description: Workflow motif that relates workflows with each other by determining whether different workflows are a composition of each other (composite workflow) or not (atomic workflow), or they have a very similar composition but work for different inputs (workflow overloading).
fields.label: Inter-workflow motif

fields.description: Data preparation motif that refers to a filtering step or set of steps. For example, A file filtered by a set of set of keywords, a table filtered by a threshold, etc.
fields.label: Filter

fields.description: Data preparation motif that refers to the step or set of steps that reorganize the input into different groups. For example, grouping a table by a certain category.
fields.label: Group

fields.description: Inter-workflow motif used to characterize workflows that are used to operate over different input parameter types. An example is performing an analysis over a String input parameter, or performing it over the contents of a specified File. Overloading is a direct response to the heterogeneity of environments in which workflows are used.
fields.label: Workflow overload

fields.description: Data, as it is originally retrieved, may need several transformations before being able to be used in a workflow step. These steps, typically known as ”Shims” [Duncan Hull et al. Treating shimantic web syndrome with ontologies. In AKT Workshop on Semantic Web Services, 2004.], can be annotated using the Data Preparation motif.
fields.label: Data preparation

fields.description: A motif is a domain independent conceptual abstraction of one or more steps of a given workflow.
fields.label: Motif

fields.description: Data preparation motif that refers to the step or group of steps in the workflow aggregating information from different sources. For example, the joining of two tables in a new one or the merging of three different files in a bigger one.
fields.label: Combine

fields.description: Data preparation motif that refers to the step or set of steps ordering the input by certain parameter. For example, a quicksort algorithm that takes an unordered vector and produces a sorted output.
fields.label: Sort

fields.description: Intra-workflow motif used to characterize the activities that require human inputs during their execution. For example, manual data curation of a table for a future step in the workflow, cleaning and filtering steps (such as selecting a specific dataset to continue the experiment), etc.
fields.label: Human interaction step

fields.description: Intra-workflow motif that refers to those groups of steps in the workflow that correspond to repetitive patterns of combining tasks. For example, if a workflow has several branches with the same sequence of repeated steps, the sequence becomes an internal macro.
fields.label: Internal macro

fields.description: Certain analysis activities that are performed via external tools or services require the submission of data to a location accessible by the service/tool (i.e., a web or a local directory respectively). In such cases the workflow contains dedicated step(s) for the upload/transfer of data to these locations. The same applies to the outputs, in which case a data download/retrieval step is used to chain the data to the next steps of the workflow.
fields.label: Data movement

fields.description: Certain activities such as analysis or visualizations could be performed through interaction with stateful (web) services that allow for creation of jobs over remote grid environments. These are typically performed via invocation of multiple operations at a service endpoint. An example would be a BLAST job submission where the service invoker is responsible to first create a job, then submit the data, check the status and retrieve the results once it has finished.
fields.label: Stateful (asynchronous) invocation

fields.description: Being able to show the results is as important as producing them in some workflows. Scientists use visualizations to show the conclusions of their experiments and to take important decisions in the pipeline itself. Therefore certain steps in workflows are dedicated to generation of plots and graph outputs from input data. The data visualization motif also includes the generation of tables and files for browsing and reading the results of the workflow.
fields.label: Data visualization

fields.description: Intra-workflow motif used to refer to activities performed by a computer. This motif applies to most of the steps of the workflow, except for those being human interaction steps.
fields.label: Computational step

fields.description: Data preparation motif that refers to the step or set of steps in the workflow retrieving only the relevant portion from the the output of a previous step. For example, retrieving the tag value of an XML fragment.
fields.label: Output extraction

fields.description: Data operation motif that refers to the step or series of steps for cleaning and curating data in a workflow. Typically these steps are undertaken by sophisticated tooling/services, or by human interactions. A data cleaning step preserves and enriches the content of data (e.g., by a user’s annotation of a result with additional information, detecting and removing inconsistencies on the data, etc.).
fields.label: Data cleaning

fields.description: Data operation motif that refers to a broad category of tasks in diverse domains. An important number of workflows are designed with the purpose of analyzing different features of input data, ranging from simple comparisons between the datasets to complex protein analysis to see whether two molecules can be docked successfully or not.
fields.label: Data analysis

fields.description:
Extended definition:

	"An Information Service is this part of an Information System that serves data/knowledge/information to customers and collects it 
	from its contributors, to manage and store it by optionally using administrators."

Please refer also this article[1] about the definition of the term 'Information Service'.

This concept is for linking a piece of information of a specific concept instance (or at least website links or other data representations 
of this concept instance), e.g. a foaf:Agent, a mo:Track or a mo:MusicArtist to a related website of a specific information service (modelled 
as individual of is:InfoService), e.g. Wikipedia, MySpace, MusicBrainz, Discogs, Last.fm, Pandora, BBC, ... . With this concept it is possible 
to describe the underlying information services of that knowledge representation more in detail, so that the client, which consumes that 
'linked data' could choose, which source it likes to use by evaluating the description of the information service of that website link or 
other data representation.
Please use for further is:InfoService instances the namespace "http://purl.org/ontology/is/inst/".


[1] https://infoserviceonto.wordpress.com/2010/06/23/what-is-an-information-service/
fields.label: Information Service

fields.description:
Distinct intellectual or artistic musical creation.
    
From the FRBR final report: A work is an abstract entity; there is no single material object one can point to as the work. We recognize the work through individual realizations or expressions of the work, but the work itself exists only in the commonality of
content between and among the various expressions of the work. When we speak of Homer's Iliad as a work, our point of reference is not a particular recitation or text of the work, but the intellectual creation that lies behind all the various expressions of the work.     

For example:

work #1 J. S. Bach's The art of the fugue

fields.description:
A single exemplar of a musical expression.
    
For example, it could be a single exemplar of a CD. This is normally an single object (a CD) possessed by somebody.

From the FRBR final report: The entity defined as item is a concrete entity. It is in many instances a single physical object (e.g., a copy of a one-volume monograph, a single audio cassette, etc.). There are instances, however, where the entity defined as item comprises more than one physical object (e.g., a monograph issued as two separately bound volumes, a recording issued on three separate compact discs, etc.).

In terms of intellectual content and physical form, an item exemplifying a manifestation is normally the same as the manifestation itself. However, variations may occur from one item to another, even when the items exemplify the same manifestation, where those variations are the result of actions external to the intent of the producer of the manifestation (e.g., damage occurring after the item was produced, binding performed by a library, etc.).
fields.label: MusicalItem

fields.description:
This entity is related to the edition/production/publication of a musical expression (musical manifestation are closely related with the music industry (their terms, concepts, definitions, methods (production, publication, etc.), etc.)
    
From the FRBR final report: The entity defined as manifestation encompasses a wide range of materials, including manuscripts, books, periodicals, maps, posters, sound recordings, films, video recordings, CD-ROMs, multimedia kits, etc. As an entity, manifestation represents all the physical objects that bear the same characteristics, in respect to both intellectual content and physical form.


Work #1 J. S. Bach's Six suites for unaccompanied cello

    * Expression #1 sound issued during the performance by Janos Starker recorded in 1963 and 1965
          o Manifestation #1 recordings released on 33 1/3 rpm sound discs in 1965 by Mercury
          o Manifestation #2 recordings re-released on compact disc in 1991 by Mercury 
    * Expression #2 sound issued during the performances by Yo-Yo Ma recorded in 1983
          o Manifestation #1 recordings released on 33 1/3 rpm sound discs in 1983 by CBS Records
          o Manifestation #2 recordings re-released on compact disc in 1992 by CBS Records 

          
Changes that occur deliberately or even inadvertently in the production process that affect the copies result, strictly speaking, in a new manifestation. A manifestation resulting from such a change may be identified as a particular "state" or "issue" of the publication.

Changes that occur to an individual copy after the production process is complete (e.g., the loss of a page, rebinding, etc.) are not considered to result in a new manifestation. That copy is simply considered to be an exemplar (or item) of the manifestation that deviates from the copy as produced.

With the entity defined as manifestation we can describe the physical characteristics of a set of items and the characteristics associated with the production and distribution of that set of items that may be important factors in enabling users to choose a manifestation appropriate to their physical needs and constraints, and to identify and acquire a copy of that manifestation.

Defining manifestation as an entity also enables us to draw relationships between specific manifestations of a work. We can use the relationships between manifestations to identify, for example, the specific publication that was used to create a microreproduction.
fields.label: musical manifestation

fields.description: Libretto
fields.label: libretto

fields.description: Super Audio Compact Disc used as medium to record a musical manifestation.
fields.label: SACD

fields.description: An analog signal.
fields.label: analogue signal

fields.description: Lyrics
fields.label: lyrics

fields.description:
A person or a group of people (or a computer :-) ), whose musical 
        creative work shows sensitivity and imagination
fields.label: music artist

fields.description: A published libretto
fields.label: published libretto

fields.description: A musical expression representing a group of signals, for example a set of masters resulting from a whole recording/mastering session.
fields.label: signal group

fields.description:
The intellectual or artistic realization of a work in the form of alpha-numeric, musical, or choreographic notation, sound, etc., or any combination of such forms.    


For example:

Work #1 Franz Schubert's Trout quintet

    * Expression #1 the composer's score
    * Expression #2 sound issued from the performance by the Amadeus Quartet and Hephzibah Menuhin on piano
    * Expression #3 sound issued from the performance by the Cleveland Quartet and Yo-Yo Ma on the cello
    * . . . . 

The Music Ontology defines the following sub-concepts of a MusicalExpression, which should be used instead of MusicalExpression itself: Score (the
result of an arrangement), Sound (produced during a performance), Signal. However, it is possible to stick to FRBR and bypass the worflow
mechanism this ontology defines by using the core FRBR properties on such objects. But it is often better to use events to interconnect such 
expressions (allowing to go deeply into the production process - `this performer was playing this particular instrument at that
particular time').
fields.label: musical expression

fields.description: Release type of a particular manifestation, such as "album" or "interview"...
fields.label: Release type

fields.description:
A movement is a self-contained part of a musical work. While individual or selected movements from a composition are sometimes performed separately, a performance of the complete work requires all the movements to be performed in succession.

Often a composer attempts to interrelate the movements thematically, or sometimes in more subtle ways, in order that the individual
movements exert a cumulative effect. In some forms, composers sometimes link the movements, or ask for them to be played without a
pause between them.
fields.label: movement

fields.description: Something available on the Bittorrent peer-2-peer filesharing network
fields.label: Torrent

fields.description: Transmission over a network  used as medium to broadcast a musical manifestation
fields.label: Stream

fields.description: Compact Disc used as medium to record a musical manifestation.
fields.label: CD

fields.description: DVD-Audio used as medium to record a musical manifestation.
fields.label: DVDA

fields.description:
Any of various devices or contrivances that can be used to produce musical tones or sound.
        
        Any taxonomy can be used to subsume this concept. The default one is one extracted by Ivan Herman
        from the Musicbrainz instrument taxonomy, conforming to SKOS. This concept holds a seeAlso link 
        towards this taxonomy.
fields.label: Instrument

fields.description: A subclass of MusicalExpression, representing a signal, for example a master signal produced by a performance and a recording.
fields.label: signal

fields.description:
Instrumentation deals with the techniques of writing music for a specific instrument, 
        including the limitations of the instrument, playing techniques and idiomatic handling of the instrument.
fields.label: instrumentation

fields.description: A specific release, with barcode, box, liner notes, cover art, and a number of records
fields.label: release

fields.description: An audio file, which may be available on a local file system or through http, ftp, etc.
fields.label: audio file

fields.description: Trade name of a company that produces musical works or expression of musical works.
fields.label: label

fields.description: Transcription event
fields.label: transcription

fields.description: A published score (subclass of MusicalManifestation)
fields.label: published score

fields.description: A published record (manifestation which first aim is to render the product of a recording)
fields.label: record

fields.description:
A show - a musical event lasting several days, in a particular venue. Examples can be
        "The Magic Flute" at the Opera Bastille, August 2005, or a musical in the west end...
fields.label: Show

fields.description: A slot in an ordered list with a fixed index.
fields.label: Slot

fields.description: An ordered list with a given length an indexed items.
fields.label: Ordered List

fields.description: A media action counter. Media actions are for example play back or skip events.
fields.label: Media Action Counter

fields.description: A playlist of specific media items, e.g. music tracks, videos or slides.
fields.label: Playlist

fields.description: A play back counter, e.g. to count the playback of a media object.
fields.label: Play Back Counter

fields.description:
A playlist slot. It could contain e.g. a music track, a video or a slide, and maybe related with some 
additional properties. However, it could maybe also included a "sub" playlist, e.g. to keep a fixed sequence of some tracks.
fields.label: Playlist Slot

fields.description: A specific skip event of something.
fields.label: Skip Event

fields.description: A skip counter, e.g. to count skip events of a media object.
fields.label: Skip Counter

fields.description:
A (sub) playlist of a fixed length and a fixed order. This concept should be used to express static relations, 
e.g. "those three music tracks must always be played in a row".
fields.label: Fixed Playlist

fields.description: A desert is a landscape or region that receives an extremely low amount of precipitation, less than enough to support growth of most plants.
fields.label: Desert

fields.description: An inland body of water.
fields.label: Lake

fields.description: A large settlement, often with some form of formal political recognition.
fields.label: City

fields.description: A natural watercourse flowing towards an ocean, sea or lake.
fields.label: River

fields.description: A ridge of land seperating two adjacent water systems.
fields.label: Watershed

fields.description: A strip of land projecting into a body of water
fields.label: Cape

fields.description: A Settlement is an area of land inhabited by humans and usually having buildings.
fields.label: Settlement

fields.description: A level area of land.
fields.label: Plain

fields.description: An area that is useful to illustrate a particular point but does not have a recognised political or cultural identity.
fields.label: Arbitrary Region

fields.description: A Road is a recognised and maintained route from one place to another that is suitable for vehicles.
fields.label: Road

fields.description: A piece of land, useful in combination with Continent, Plate and others.
fields.label: Landmass

fields.description: A large body of salt water, usually connected to an ocean.
fields.label: Sea

fields.description: A region of governance.
fields.label: Province

fields.description: A geological plate, a piece of the earth’s crust. Useful for geological descriptions involving the movement and separation of continents.
fields.label: Plate

fields.description: A politically or culturally recognised area.
fields.label: Region

fields.description: A hill is a landform that extends above the surrounding terrain.
fields.label: Hill

fields.description: An indentation to a shoreline, a body of water enclosed but with a large mouth to a wider body of water.
fields.label: Bay

fields.description: A settlement and geographic area, less formally recognised than a town.
fields.label: Township

fields.description: An area of regional governance stemming from the geographical area associated with a church.
fields.label: Parish

fields.description: The widened area of a river as it opens to meet the sea or ocean.
fields.label: Estuary

fields.description: A narrow strip of land, bounded by water on two sides, and connecting two larger landmasses.
fields.label: Isthmus

fields.description: A region of governance, often self-governed.
fields.label: Municipality

fields.description: A volcano is a crack in the Earth's crust that allows lava and hot gases to escape.
fields.label: Volcano

fields.description: The shore of a body of water, usually sandy or pebbly.
fields.label: Beach

fields.description: A region considered to be the territory of a recognised political state.
fields.label: Country

fields.description: A flat highland, a large area of flat land higher than the surrounding land.
fields.label: Plateau

fields.description: A slow-moving mass of ice.
fields.label: Glacier

fields.description: A major body of salt water.
fields.label: Ocean

fields.description: A man-made or natural lake used for the storage and regulation of a water supply.
fields.label: Reservoir

fields.description: A Boundary resource specifies a sequence of points which, if joined, give the boundary of a geographical area. The sequence may be a serious of resources, each with a latitude and longitude, or a series of points using the datatype place:latlong. If the final point is the same as the first then the boundary is considered to be a closed area, whereas if the first and last points differ the boundary is considered to be a border line.
fields.label: Boundary

fields.description: A settlement smaller than a city but larger than a village.
fields.label: Town

fields.description: An administrative region of governance.
fields.label: Borough

fields.description: A small human settlement.
fields.label: Village

fields.description: A Path is a recognised and maintained route from one place to another that is suitable for pedestrians.
fields.label: Path

fields.description: A long elevation or striation in the land.
fields.label: Ridge

fields.description: A region of governance.
fields.label: District

fields.description: A steep high face of rock.
fields.label: Cliff

fields.description: A Hamlet is a small human settlement consisting of just a few dwellings.
fields.label: Hamlet

fields.description: A narrow channel of a sea joining two larger bodies of water.
fields.label: Strait

fields.description: A depressed area of land, often between mountains and often containing a river.
fields.label: Valley

fields.description: Part of a sea or ocean that is partially enclosed by land. Like a bay but larger.
fields.label: Gulf

fields.description: A mountain is a large landform that stretches above the surrounding land in a limited area usually in the form of a peak. A mountain is generally steeper than a hill.
fields.label: Mountain

fields.description: A landmass projecting out into a body of water.
fields.label: Peninsula

fields.description: A large landmass recognised by convention as a continent.
fields.label: Continent

fields.description: A county is a land area of local governance within a country. A county may have cities and towns within its area.
fields.label: County

fields.description: A landmass surrounded entirely by water.
fields.label: Island

fields.description: A State is a land area of governance within a country. A state may have counties, cities and towns within its area.
fields.label: State

fields.description: Services that use a Web medium.
fields.label: Web

fields.description: Services that use a radio medium.
fields.label: Radio

fields.description:
The format of a particular version (should be of the episode, btw).
		Instances of this concept include documentaries, talk shows, animation, etc.
fields.label: Format

fields.description: Subtitles associated to a particular version.
fields.label: Subtitle

fields.description:
An `original' version, the legacy version of
		a particular episode.
fields.label: Original version

fields.description: A particular episode, eg. `Flight of the Conchords, first episode of the first season'
fields.label: Episode

fields.description: A programme, can either be a brand, a series or an episode
fields.label: Programme

fields.description:
A broadcast event.
		Subsumes the event concept defined in
		the event ontology.
		A broadcast is associated to a service, and to a
		particular version of an episode.
fields.label: Broadcast

fields.description:
A service is a particular channel on which a broadcast occurrs.
		Instances of this concept include BBC Radio Wales, BBC Radio 4, BBC News, etc.
fields.label: Service

fields.description: A shortened version.
fields.label: Shortened version

fields.description: Radio services aiming at a national coverage.
fields.label: National radio

fields.description:
Specifies a broadcast as being a 
		repeat.
fields.label: Repeat

fields.description: Radio services aiming at a local coverage.
fields.label: Local radio

fields.description: Radio services aiming at a regional coverage.
fields.label: Regional radio

fields.description: A serie, eg. `Flight of the Conchors, first season'
fields.label: Serie

fields.description:
A particular version of an episode.
		Such versions include shortened ones, audio described ones
		or ones that holds sign language.
fields.label: Version

fields.description: A version holding sign language.
fields.label: Sign language

fields.description:
Specifies a broadcast as being the 
		first one of a particular version.
fields.label: First broadcast

fields.description: A brand, eg. `Flight of the Conchords'
fields.label: Brand

fields.description: A version holding an audio description.
fields.label: Audio description

fields.description: Services that use a television medium.
fields.label: TV

fields.description: A recommendation of something for someone or a specific audience by a recommender.
fields.label: Recommendation

fields.description: A ranked recommendation that includes an ordered list of recommendations.
fields.label: Ranked Recommendation

fields.description: A network is a grouping of sim:Associations. The associations that comprise a network are specified using a series of sim:edge predicates.
fields.label: Network

fields.description: A concept for representing the method used to derive association or similarity statements.
fields.label: Association Method

fields.description: An abstract class indicating a directed association of influence where the subject entity has influenced the object entity.
fields.label: Influence

fields.description: An abstract class to define some association between things. Entities share an association if they are somehow inter-connected. Generally a directed association should have at lease one sim:subject property and one sim:object property or an undirected association should have at least two sim:element properties, however this is not a requirement and intentionally left out of the model.
fields.label: Association

fields.description: An abstract class to define similarity between two or more things.  Entities share a similarity if they share some common characteristics of interest.  A similarity is a special type of association.
fields.label: Similarity

fields.description: Places an Event in an EventList, with index and neighbouring Event information.
fields.label: EventSlot

fields.description: A story that may be told, contain other stories, and have a sequence of events.
fields.label: Story

fields.description: An interpretation of something in the context of a story, given some supporting material. This is the viewpoint of the interpretation's creator, and may assert statements about the item.
fields.label: Interpretation

fields.description: Contains a set of statements in the form of an RDF graph, thus allowing for interpretations to assert beliefs about the state of the system.
fields.label: Assertion

fields.description: Provides a means to create an ordered list of events that occur within a story - effectively a pairing of an Event and a numeric position.
fields.label: EventList

fields.description: A newsworthy event. An un-disputable real world event.
fields.label: Event

fields.description: Attribution of a storyline used for attributing the interpretation of the storyline to some agent. An interface class, that doesn't restrict the implementation of an attribution.
fields.label: Attribution

fields.description: A storyline slot, used as a container for storyline components.
fields.label: StorylineSlot

fields.description: The topic of a storyline. An interface to some concept in a knowledge domain.
fields.label: Topic

fields.description: A news storyline.
fields.label: Storyline

fields.description: An abstract parent class of storyline components.
fields.label: StorylineComponent

fields.description: A weight class to enable timestamped weights.
fields.label: Weight

fields.description: An event concept for describing dynamics of interests, e.g. weight changes, periods of interest.
fields.label: Interest Dynamics

fields.description: A complex interest, which can have interest dynamics etc.
fields.label: Complex Interest

fields.description: A weighted interest object
fields.label: Weighted Interest

fields.description: A concept for describing scales for weights.
fields.label: Scale

fields.description: A context object
fields.label: Context

fields.description: A family is a scientific grouping of closely related organisms. It has smaller groups, called genera and species, within it. A family can have a lot of members or only a few. Examples of families include the cats (Felidae), the gulls (Laridae) and the grasses (Poaceae).
fields.label: Family

fields.description: A phylum - also known as a division when referring to plants - is a scientfic way of grouping together related organisms. All the members of a phylum have a common ancestor and anatomical similarities. For instance, all the arthropods have external skeletons. Phlya are large groups and are further subdivided into classes, orders, families and so on.
fields.label: Phylum

fields.description: Morphology is anything to do with what a plant or animal looks like - its size, shape, colour or structure.
fields.label: Morphology

fields.description: A collection of resources, including documents, multimedia files, programme clips and their associated taxa, which aims to showcase a particular aspect of natural history film-making, or illustrate aspects of the natural world. A collection provides an alternate way to organize content over and above the basic taxonomic hierarchy.
fields.label: Collection

fields.description: Generic class defining a biological species
fields.label: species

fields.description: Ecosystem roles are about the part an animal or plant plays in sustaining or maintaining the habitat around them. Bees, for example, pollinate flowers, without which those plants would not produce fruits or seeds. Other species, such as dung beetles, play a vital role in keeping grasslands clear of animal waste and recycling valuable resources.
fields.label: Ecosystem Role

fields.description: Approximately 71% of the Earth's surface is covered by the oceans, an area of some 223698816km/sq. Although marine life evolved around three billion years before life on land, marine habitats are relatively poorly studied and much of the ocean's depths remains unexplored.
fields.label: Marine Habitat

fields.description: Freshwater habitats include bogs, ponds, lakes, rivers and streams. About 3% of Earth's water is freshwater, but this includes the water locked up in the ice caps and trapped in rocks and soil as groundwater. Only a tiny fraction (0.014%) is surface water in the form of rivers, lakes and swamps.
fields.label: Freshwater Habitat

fields.description: Feeding habits describe the dominant diet of a particular species or group of species, and how they go about obtaining it.
fields.label: Feeding Habit

fields.description: A habitat, or biome, is the type of environment in which plant and animals live. Habitat is dictated by what kinds of plants grow there, the climate and the geography. Rainforest, coral reefs and the tundra are all habitats where particular kinds of plants and animals might be found.
fields.label: Habitat

fields.description: A genus is a scientific way of showing that species are very closed related to each other. In fact the first word of the species' scientific name is its genus. So for lions (Panthera leo), Panthera is the genus and tells us that they are closely related to tigers (Panthera tigris), because they share the name
fields.label: Genus

fields.description: A category in the IUCN red list, 2001.
fields.label: Red List Status

fields.description: A class is a scientific way to group related organisms together, some examples of classes being jellyfish, reptiles and sea urchins. Classes are big groups and contain within them smaller groupings called orders, families, genera and species.
fields.label: Class

fields.description: An adaptation is any feature of an animal or plant which makes it better suited for a particular habitat or to do a particular task. For instance, being streamlined is an adaptation to swimming fast and being able to survive on very little water is an adaptation to life in the desert.
fields.label: Adaptation

fields.description: Behavioural pattern describes an animal's dominant way of life. Arboreal animals, for example, live in trees and nocturnal animals are active at night.
fields.label: Behavioural Pattern

fields.description: Ecozones are a method of dividing up the Earth's surface. Each ecozone is a large area that contains a number of habitats, which are linked by the evolutionary history of the animals and plants within them. For instance one ecozone is Australasia, because its marsupials evolved in isolation to mammals in the rest of the world.
fields.label: Ecozone

fields.description: Conservation status as described by the IUCN Red List. Will typically have a number of properties including an official IUCN status, population trend, and a year of assessment.
fields.label: Conservation Status

fields.description: Social behaviour is all about how an animal interacts with members of its own species. For instance, does it live in a colony or on its own, does it fight to be top of the pecking order, or does it try to keep strangers away from its home?
fields.label: Social Behaviour

fields.description: Survival strategies include adaptations to changes in the organisms environment, including: hibernation, abscission and migration.
fields.label: Survival Strategy

fields.description: A taxonomic name, describing the structure and provenance of a taxonomic name.
fields.label: Taxon Name

fields.description: Locomotion is how an animal gets around - for instance by swimming, flying or climbing.
fields.label: Locomotion

fields.description: An order is a scientific way to categorise related organisms. An order is a smaller grouping than a class, but bigger than a family or genus. Examples of orders are willows, cockroaches and primates.
fields.label: Order

fields.description: Generic concept for a taxonomic rank such as a Genus or Species.
fields.label: Taxonomic Rank

fields.description: Kingdoms are the major categories into which scientists divide up all living things. The main kingdoms are animals, plants, fungi and bacteria, although there are others. Each kingdom has its own suite of defining characteristics - for instance plants have rigid cell walls, whilst animals do not.
fields.label: Kingdom

fields.description: Organisms that are adapted to extremes (known as Extremophiles) are organisms that thrives in and even may require physically or geochemically extreme conditions that are detrimental to the majority of life on Earth.
fields.label: Adapted to Extremes

fields.description: Terrestrial habitats include forests, grasslands, deserts and rainforests. They are typically defined by factors such as plant structure (trees and grasses), leaf types (eg broadleaf and needleleaf), plant spacing (forest, woodland, savanna) and climate.
fields.label: Terrestrial Habitat

fields.description: Animal Intelligence or animal cognition is the title given to a modern approach to the mental capacities of non-human animals. It has developed out of comparative psychology, but has also been strongly influenced by the approach of ethology, behavioral ecology, and evolutionary psychology.
fields.label: Animal Intelligence

fields.description: Predation is catching and killing an animal in order to eat it. The prey can be chased, ambushed or caught in a trap such as a spider's web.
fields.label: Predation Strategy

fields.description: Reproduction covers all the tactics and behaviours involved in obtaining a mate, conceiving the next generation and successfully raising them. It includes everything from plants being pollinated, to stags fighting over hinds, to lionesses babysitting their sisters' cubs.
fields.label: Reproduction Strategy

fields.description: Communication and senses are how an organism perceives the world - for instance through scent or sight - and how it sends messages or warnings to others.
fields.label: Communication Adaptation

fields.description: An organism's Life Cycle describes the stages in an organisms development including metamorphosis, courtship displays and parental care..
fields.label: Life Cycle

fields.description: A concept for describing scales for weights.
fields.label: Scale

fields.description: A weight class to enable timestamped (etc.) weights.
fields.label: Weight

fields.description: Class to represent the most common relative directions. Possible values include: left, right, forward, backward, up, down.
fields.label: RelativeDirection

fields.description: A generic Fridge with no Freezer unit as a product type
fields.label: Fridge

fields.description: Class to represent the European Union energy label codas of a fridge. Possible values go from A+++ to G.
fields.label: EnergyRatingEU

fields.description: Class to represent the different styles of fridge/freezers. Possible values include: french-door, side-by-side, top-freezer, bottom-freezer, single-door.
fields.label: StyleOfUnit

fields.description: A generic Fridge/Freezer as a product type
fields.label: FridgeFreezer

fields.description: A generic dedicated Freezer (with no Fridge unit) as a product type
fields.label: Freezer

fields.description: Class to represent the different types of body frames of a fridge/freezer. Possible values include: built-in, free-standing.
fields.label: TypeOfBody

fields.description: Class to represent the range of room temperatures that a fridge/freezer can operate. Possible values include: N, SN, ST, T.
fields.label: ClimateClass

fields.description: An RDF document describing a specific organisation.
fields.label: Organization Profile Document

fields.description: A capability of a facility or organization. This is subtley different from a service, in that it means that it is capable of performing a certain task or technique. It may be useful to list capabilities when bidding for research contracts and grants.
fields.label: Capability

fields.description: A service. This term has been defined for the purposes of defining services offered by university research facilities, but isn't restricted to universities or research. This term is in testing and may be superceeded by the Cerif vocab.
fields.label: Service

fields.description: An item of equipment. This term is in testing and may be superceeded by the Cerif vocab.
fields.label: Equipment

fields.description: A facility. A facility is a grouping of equipment and/or people that can perform specific tasks. This term has been coined to use in relation to research facilites at universities, but is not restricted to only research facilities. This term is in testing and may be superceeded by the Cerif vocab.
fields.label: Facility

fields.description: An "address representation" as defined in the data specifications of the EU INSPIRE Directive. The locn:addressId property may be used to link this Address to other representations. This address extends the address with additional information
fields.label: ExtendedAddress

fields.description:
This is the key class for the Business Core Vocabulary and represents a 
    business that is legally registered. In many countries there is a single registry although in others, 
    such as Spain and Germany, multiple registries exist. A Legal Entity is able to trade, is 
    legally liable for its actions, accounts, tax affairs etc. It is a sub class of org:FormalOrganization
    which covers a wider range of entities, such as charities.
fields.label: Organization

fields.description: Denotes a role that a Person or other Agent can take in an public service. Instances of this class describe the abstract role; to denote a specific instance of a person playing that role in a specific public service use an instance of `Permission` that is linked with the formal rules `Rule`.
fields.label: Role

fields.description:
The Conceptual Model includes a 'Code' datatype that is used for the types of relation and membership properties. This is expressed using the SKOS vocabulary with a particular 'code' usually being a oslo:Code which is a skos:Concept that is part of a scheme. The intention is that the oslo:Code class be used as follows;

  • for the content property, use skos:notation
  • the 'list' property will be taken care of by means of the skos:inScheme property;
  • the list agency property is likely to be applied to the scheme as a whole for which dcterms:creator is appropriate;
  • the list version property can be fulfilled using schema:version (see http://schema.org/CreativeWork)
fields.label: Code

fields.description: An "address representation" as defined in the data specifications of the EU INSPIRE Directive. The locn:addressId property may be used to link this Address to other representations. This address extends the address with additional information
fields.label: BasicAddress

fields.description: Status of Public Service
fields.label: Status

fields.description: Denotes a the permission of a role. Should be linked with a formal rule.
fields.label: Permission

fields.description: A relation between two persons
fields.label: PersonRelation

fields.description:
This is the key class for the Business Core Vocabulary and represents a 
    business that is legally registered. In many countries there is a single registry although in others, 
    such as Spain and Germany, multiple registries exist. A Legal Entity is able to trade, is 
    legally liable for its actions, accounts, tax affairs etc. It is a sub class of org:FormalOrganization
    which covers a wider range of entities, such as charities.
fields.label: Membership

fields.description: Information related to a Parcel Address or Label
fields.label: Parcel

fields.description: Information related to a Building
fields.label: Building

fields.description: A relation between two organizations
fields.label: OrganizationnRelation

fields.description: A relation between two agents
fields.label: Relation

fields.description: This class represents any object that has an address.
fields.label: ResidenceObject

fields.description: Základní třída pro popis nabídky dodavatele
fields.label: Tender

fields.description: Třída specifikující že jediným kritériem pro posuzování nabídek dodavatelů je nejnižší cena
fields.label: Lowest price is the only contract award criterion

fields.description: Basic class for decribing a public contract
fields.label: Public contract

fields.description: Class for description of criteria combination used for tender evaluation
fields.label: Combination of contract award criteria

fields.description: Třída pro popis jednoho kritéria a jeho váhy.
fields.label: Contract award criterion

fields.description: An RSS image.
fields.label: Image

fields.description: An RSS text input.
fields.label: Text Input

fields.description: An RSS information channel.
fields.label: Channel

fields.description: An RSS item.
fields.label: Item

fields.description: A record that uniquely references a particular publication (or a work in preparation for publication). Each bibliographic record is a set of entities describing aspects of the referenced work, for example authors, title, journal, publication year, DOI, ISSN, publisher and copyright information. The FRBR expression of a bibliographic record is a bibliographic reference, which usually contains only a sub-set of these entities, ordered in a particular way that corresponds to the house style of the publication in which it occurs.
fields.label: bibliographic record

fields.description: An expression of a bibliographic record in a specific format, that references a particular publication (or a work in preparation for publication).
