Each bibliographic reference is a list of items containing entities that describe aspects of the referenced work - for example authors, title, journal, publication year - selected from the bibliographic record.
fields.label: bibliographic reference

fields.description: A list used to describe the bibliography of a research paper, a journal article, a book, a book chapter or similar publication.
fields.label: reference list

fields.description: A collection of bibliographic records, each of which references a publication (or a work in preparation for publication). Examples of bibliographic collections include a collection of the bibliographic records of all the publications that a single individual has authored, or a collection of those bibliographic records to be included in a research paper, where they are expressed as a reference list.
fields.label: bibliographic collection

fields.description: An ordered list of bibliographic items, each of which contains a bibliographic reference.
fields.label: bibliographic list

fields.description: A catalogue of the bibliographic holdings of a library.
fields.label: library catalogue

fields.description: The number of times a work has been cited globally, as determined from a particular bibliographic information source on a particular date.
fields.label: global citation count

fields.description: A source of information about bibliographic citations, such as Google Scholar, Web of Science or Scopus.
fields.label: bibliographic information source

fields.description: A list containing only in-text reference pointers denoting the specific bibliographic references to which the list pertains.
fields.label: in-text reference pointer list

fields.description: This class describes all the list items that must be used in the context of an in-text reference pointer list.
fields.label: in-text reference pointer list item

fields.description:
The in-text reference pointer is a textual element, usually embedded at the end of a phrase or sentence within the text of a document, that denotes a specific bibliographic reference present in the reference list of that document. For example, if the item in the reference list is: 

4.  Ko AI, Reis MG, Ribeiro Dourado CM, Johnson WD Jr, Riley LW (1999). Urban epidemic of severe leptospirosis in Brazil. Salvador Leptospirosis Study Group. Lancet 354: 820-825.

the in-text reference pointer to this paper in a journal article may be manifested in a number of ways:	

Numerically, for example by using the numeral 4 in superscript or between square brackets, thus: [4].  Such numerical in-text 
reference pointers are frequently aggregated, e.g. [4, 5, 6-9].  In such cases, the missing pointers to references 7 and 8 are inferred (and should be added explicitly to the XML mark-up at this point in the text!). 

Or by use of the author names (or the first author's name plus et al.) and the publication year in parentheses, thus: (Ko et al., 1999). 

Or, less commonly, by the use of a code, e.g. by specifying the first surname letter of the first three author of the cited work followed by the last two digits of the year of publication, this string of characters being enclosed within square brackets, thus: [KRR99].
fields.label: in-text reference pointer

fields.description: An in-text reference pointer list that pertains to exactly one bibliographic reference.
fields.label: single reference pointer list

fields.description: A description in a research paper documenting the specialized methods used in the work described. This description is often combined with a description of the materials used, in a section entitled 'Methods and Materials', 'Experimental' or a related term.
fields.label: methods

fields.description: Information describing a dataset held in an external database or repository and including a reference to it, such as a database ID or an accession number.
fields.label: dataset description

fields.description: An element of a document that carries out a rhetorical function.
fields.label: discourse element

fields.description: A reference to a specific part of the document, or to another publication.
fields.label: reference

fields.description: Text added after the signature of a letter, or sometimes after the main body of an essay or book.
fields.label: postscript

fields.description: A description of the roles played by an author in the publication.
fields.label: author contribution

fields.description: Information describing a person and his or her life history and contributions.
fields.label: biography

fields.description: Text in which the author names the person or people for whom he/she has written the document, or to whose memory it is dedicated.
fields.label: dedication

fields.description: The authors' critical review of current knowledge by specific reference to others' work, both in terms of substantive findings and theoretical and methodological contributions to a particular topic. This description is often included within the introduction section.
fields.label: related work

fields.description: A description of a model used or produced by the work described in the publication.
fields.label: model

fields.description: A textual description of data used or produced in the work which the document describes, or the data themselves.
fields.label: data

fields.description: The report of the specific findings of an investigation, given without discussion or conclusion being drawn.
fields.label: results

fields.description: Text accompanying another item, such as a picture.
fields.label: caption

fields.description: Informative text that explicitly explains another item, such as a figure or a table.
fields.label: legend

fields.description: A piece of writing at the end of a work of literature or drama, usually used to bring closure to the work.
fields.label: epilogue

fields.description: An initial description which states the purpose and goals of the following writing, and, in the case of journal articles, typically includes background information on the research topic and a review of related work in the area.
fields.label: introduction

fields.description: Information describing supplementary information relating to the document, including references or links to the relevant supplementary information.
fields.label: supplementary information description

fields.description: Usually part of the preface, or a separate section in its own right, often as part of the back matter, it acknowledges those, including funding agencies, who contributed to the undertaking of a research project described in a publication, or to the creation of the work in some way. In scientific articles, the acknowledgements are usually placed as a separated section immediately following the Discussion or Conclusions.
fields.label: acknowledgements

fields.description: A piece of writing at the beginning of a work of literature or drama, usually used to set the scene or to introduce the work.
fields.label: prologue

fields.description: A reference, usually contained in a footnote or a bibliographic reference list, that refer to another publication, such as a journal article, a book, a book chapter or a Web site. The inclusion of the bibliographic reference in a publication constitutes the performative act of bibliographic citation.
fields.label: bibliographic reference

fields.description: A proposal for new investigation to be undertaken in order to continue and advance the work described in the publication.
fields.label: future work

fields.description: Information describing an external resource and including a reference to that resource.
fields.label: external resource description

fields.description: A description in a research paper documenting the specialized materials used in the work described. This description is often combined with a description of the methods used, in a section entitled 'Methods and Materials', 'Experimental' or a related term.
fields.label: materials

fields.description: A supplemental addition to the main work. It may contain data, more detailed information about methods and materials, or provide additional detail concerning the information found in the main work.
fields.label: appendix

fields.description: The central principle part of a document, that contains the real content. It may be subdivided hierarchically by the use of chapters and sections.
fields.label: body matter

fields.description:
A line in poetry is a unit of language into which a poem is divided which operates on principles which are distinct from and not necessarily coincident with grammatical structures, such as the sentence or clauses in sentences.

A distinct numbered group of lines in verse is normally called a stanza.
fields.label: line

fields.description: A block containing a label for the chapter, that may include the chapter number.
fields.label: chapter label

fields.description: A block quotation (also known as a long quotation or extract) is a quotation in a written document which is set off from the main text as a distinct paragraph, which is typically distinguished visually using indentation, a different font, or smaller size. Block quotations are used for longer passages than run-in quotations (which are set off with quotation marks).
fields.label: block quotation

fields.description: A container of a semantic subdivision of a document. For example, chapters of a novel may be grouped into distinct parts that may be named 'Part 1', 'Part 2', etc., 'Book 1', 'Book 2', etc., or 'Genesis', 'Exodus', etc.
fields.label: part

fields.description: A space within a document that contains one or more formulae.
fields.label: formula box

fields.description: A section describing how the document came into being, or how the idea for it was developed. The preface may contains acknowledgements. The preface to a later edition of the work often explains in what respect that edition differs from previous ones.
fields.label: preface

fields.description: A block containing a label for the table box, that may include the table number.
fields.label: table label

fields.description: A word, phrase or sentence that precedes and indicates the subject of a document or a document component - e.g., a book, a report, a news article, a chapter, a section or a table.
fields.label: title

fields.description: A list of items each representing a reference to a specific part of the same document, or to another publication.
fields.label: list of references

fields.description: The title of a chapter.
fields.label: chapter title

fields.description: A quotation with a complex structure, that is included inline and is usually enclosed within quotation marks.
fields.label: complex run-in quotation

fields.description: A space within a document that contains a table and its caption.
fields.label: table box

fields.description: A block containing a label for the section, that may include the section number.
fields.label: section label

fields.description: A space within a document that contains a figure and its caption.
fields.label: figure box

fields.description: A list of items, each denoting a contributor to a publication such as an encyclopedia or a text book, where such contributions are insufficient to warrant classification as author.
fields.label: list of contributors

fields.description: An explanatory or alternative title of a publication. For example, Mary Shelley uses the alternative title 'The Modern Prometheus' to hint at the theme of her most famous novel 'Frankenstein'; Nick Efford uses the subtitle 'a practical introduction using Java' to qualify the title of his book 'Digital Image Processing'.
fields.label: subtitle

fields.description: A list of items each denoting an author of a particular publication.
fields.label: list of authors

fields.description: A section of the document listing all the chapters and sections, identified by their titles and referenced to their locations in the document. The table of contents may include a list of the front-matter and back-matter items, in addition to the body-matter items.  Where the document is a journal or magazine issue, the table of content lists the constituent items contained in that issue, typically by title, authors and first page number.
fields.label: table of contents

fields.description: The subtitle of a chapter.
fields.label: chapter subtitle

fields.description: The final principle part of a document, in which is usually found the bibliography, index, appendixes, etc.
fields.label: back matter

fields.description: A rectangle space within a page that contains an object and its related caption.
fields.label: captioned box

fields.description: A section in a book or report, usually written by someone other than the author, that introduces or commends the document to the reader. It may include description of the interaction between the writer of the foreword and the author.
fields.label: foreword

fields.description: A logical division of the text, usually numbered and/or titled, which may contain subsections.
fields.label: section

fields.description: The subtitle of a section.
fields.label: section subtitle

fields.description: A section containing a list of references to information on the named topic of importance to the content of the document. The references may be to page numbers, paragraph numbers, section numbers or chapter numbers within the document.
fields.label: index

fields.description: A section of the document listing all the tables, identified by their titles and referenced to their locations in the document.
fields.label: list of tables

fields.description: A communication object comprising one or more graphics, drawings, images, or other visual representations..
fields.label: figure

fields.description: A list, usually within a bibliography, of all the references within the citing document that refer to  journal articles, books, book chapters, Web sites or similar publications.
fields.label: bibliographic reference list

fields.description: A block containing a label for the figure box, that may include the figure number.
fields.label: figure label

fields.description: A brief description of publication or production notes relevant to the document.
fields.label: colophon

fields.description: A textual quotation that is included inline and is usually enclosed within quotation marks.
fields.label: simple run-in quotation

fields.description: A document section containing a list of bibliographic references.
fields.label: bibliography

fields.description: A block containing text, that may include a number (e.g., "Chapter Three", "3.2", "Figure 1", "Table"), used to identify an item within the document, for example a chapter, a figure, a section or a table.
fields.label: label

fields.description: A unit within a larger poem. A stanza consists of a grouping of lines, set off by a vertical space from other stanzas, that usually has a set pattern of meter and rhyme.
fields.label: stanza

fields.description: A list of items, each denoting an organization or institution related to the publication, for example the authors' affiliations, or the suppliers of information, software, equipment or consumables used in the work described in the publication.
fields.label: list of organizations

fields.description: A piece of text defined by a start point and an end point.
fields.label: text chunk

fields.description: A principle division of the body matter of a large document, such as a book, a report or a legislative document.
fields.label: chapter

fields.description: An expression in natural language forming a single grammatical unit. A sentence minimally consists of a subject and an intransitive verb, or a subject, a transitive verb and an object, and may include additional dependent clauses. In written text, a sentence is always terminated by a full stop. A sentence can include words grouped meaningfully to express a statement, a question, an exclamation, a request or a command.
fields.label: sentence

fields.description: A structure within a sentence that permits the author to make a comment or to cite another publication in support of the text, or both. A footnote is normally flagged by a superscript number immediately following that portion of the text to which it relates. For convenience of reading, the text of the footnote is usually printed at the bottom of the page or at the end of a text.
fields.label: footnote

fields.description: An enumeration of items.
fields.label: list

fields.description: The title of a section.
fields.label: section title

fields.description: A set of definitions of words or phrases of importance to the work, normally alphabetized. In longer works of fiction, the entries may contains places and characters.
fields.label: glossary

fields.description: A section of the document listing all the figures, identified by their titles and referenced to their locations in the document. May also be referred to as 'List of illustrations'.
fields.label: list of figures

fields.description: A set of data arranged in cells within rows and columns.
fields.label: table

fields.description: A literary device that is often found at the end of a piece of literature. It generally covers the story of how the book came into being, or how the idea for the book was developed. Alternatively, it may be written by someone other than the author of the book, and may discuss the work's historical or cultural context, if the work is being reissued many years after its original publication.
fields.label: afterword

fields.description: A list of items each denoting an agent, such as an author, a contributor or an organization, related to a particular publication.
fields.label: list of agents

fields.description: A self-contained unit of discourse that deals with a particular point or idea. Paragraphs contains one or more sentences. The start of a paragraph is indicated by beginning on a new line, which may be indented or separated by a small vertical space by the preceding paragraph.
fields.label: paragraph

fields.description: A space within a document that contains textual content relating to, quoting from or expanding upon the main text. Usually a textbox is delimited by a border or use of a background colour distinct from that of the main text.
fields.label: text box

fields.description: The initial principle part of a document, usually containing self-referential metadata. In a book, this typically includes its title, authors, publisher, publication date, ISBN and copyright declaration, together with the preface, foreword, table of content, etc. In a journal article, the front matter is normally restricted to the title, authors and the authors' affiliation details, although the latter may alternatively be included in a footnote or the back matter. In books, the front matter pages may be numbered in lowercase Roman numerals.
fields.label: front matter

fields.description: A unit of information expressed in mathematical, chemical or logical symbols and language.
fields.label: formula

fields.description: A print book with a cover made of paper or paperboard, usually held together with glue rather than stitches or staples.
fields.label: paperback

fields.description: It is a manifestation in a particular digital format (such as PDF) of a particular expression.
fields.label: digital document

fields.description: A database in which the data are arranged in tables according to their common characteristics, with relationships between the tables being defined by a relational model or schema. A relational database is highly optimized for performance, and is queried using a database query language such as SQL (Structured Query Language).  The software used to create a relational database is called a relational database management system (RDBMS).
fields.label: relational database

fields.description: An editorial published in an issue of a magazine.
fields.label: magazine editorial

fields.description: An information object that represents data as a series of variations in some measurable physical quantity, such as voltage or waveform.
fields.label: analog information object

fields.description: A visual representation other than text, including all types of moving image and still image.
fields.label: image

fields.description: An alphabetically-ordered list of words and phrases ('headings') and associated pointers ('locators') to where useful material relating to that heading can be found in a document.
fields.label: index

fields.description: A digital item containing information in computer-readable form encoded in a particular format.
fields.label: computer file

fields.description: A collection of related facts, often expressed in numerical form and encoded in a defined structure.
fields.label: dataset

fields.description: The physical or electronic realization of a patent.
fields.label: patent document

fields.description: A formal correction to an error introduced by the author into a previously published document, typically published as a journal item in a subsequent issue of the journal, or as a separate loose-leaf sheet inserted into a book.
fields.label: corrigendum

fields.description: Metadata describing the work itself, including for example the name of the creator(s), the title of the work, and the data and place of its creation.
fields.label: entity metadata

fields.description: A recorded static visual representation. This class of image includes diagrams, drawings, graphs, graphic designs, plans, maps, photographs and prints.
fields.label: still image

fields.description: Standard bibliographic metadata describing an expression of a work.  To take the example of a journal article, bibliographic metadata typically include the authors' names, the date of publication, the title of the article, the journal name and volume number, the first and last page numbers, and the Digital Object Identifier (DOI).
fields.label: bibliographic metadata

fields.description: A means of storing information in digital form, involving binary encoding of data in 0s and 1s, e.g. a computer random access memory, hard disc, USB stick, CD, DVD or digital magnetic tape.
fields.label: digital storage medium

fields.description: Information communicated personally by verbal or written means from one individual to one or more another persons or organizations.
fields.label: personal communication

fields.description: A document containing the case for support for a particular project, usually contained within a grant application document but sometimes distributed separately, without the financial and organizational information that the grant application document also contains.
fields.label: case for support document

fields.description: A clinical guideline is a recommendation on the appropriate treatment and care of people with a specific disease or condition, based on the best available evidence, designed to help healthcare professionals in their work.
fields.label: clinical guideline

fields.description: A piece of writing on a particular subject.
fields.label: essay

fields.description: A thesis reporting a research project undertaken as part of an undergraduate course of education leading to a bachelor's degree.
fields.label: bachelor's thesis

fields.description: An information object that represents data in binary form, encoding the data as a series of zeroes and ones.
fields.label: digital information object

fields.description: A collaborative service, usually maintained by a project team or group, providings easy-to-edit web pages that can be used to accumulate related information for shared use by the group and/ or publication.
fields.label: wiki

fields.description: A literary creative work, such as a novel, play, poem or song.
fields.label: artistic work

fields.description: A passage of speech selected from a larger verbal or written expression for use in another expression, with specific attribution to its original source, and usually demarkated by quotation marks and / or by placing it in a separate indented paragraph.  [Note: Use fabio:Excerpt to indicate a segment or passage selected from another expression that is not a passage of speech.]
fields.label: quotation

fields.description: An article that contains a review.
fields.label: review article

fields.description: A document containing a project report, intended to be delivered to a customer or funding agency describing the results achieved within a specific project.
fields.label: deliverable

fields.description: An artistic work written with an intensity or beauty of language more characteristic of poetry than of prose.
fields.label: poem

fields.description: Information manifested in a wiki.
fields.label: wiki entry

fields.description: A publication issued on a regular and ongoing basis as a series of issues, each issue comprising separate periodical items, for example editorials, articles, news items and/or other writings.
fields.label: periodical

fields.description: A segment or passage selected from a larger expression for use in another expression, usually with specific attribution to its original source.
fields.label: excerpt

fields.description: A defined chapter of a book, usually with a separate title or number.
fields.label: book chapter

fields.description: An editorial published in an issue of a newspaper.
fields.label: newspaper editorial

fields.description: A collection of selected literary or scholastics works, for example poems, short stories, plays or research papers.
fields.label: antology

fields.description: A particular published  issue of a magazine, identified by date, and sometimes also by place (e.g. 'West Coast edition') or language (e.g. 'Spanish edition').
fields.label: magazine issue

fields.description: A formal written request for financial support from a grant-giving body in support of a project, for example an academic research project.  (See also fabio:CaseForSupport.)
fields.label: grant application

fields.description: A non-serial document that is complete in one volume or a designated finite number of volumes.  A book published by a publisher is usually  identified by an International Standard Book Number (ISBN), and may be manifested as a physical printed publication on paper bound in a hard or soft cover, or in electronic format as an 'e-book'.
fields.label: book

fields.description: A set of words, either consituting a language, or more specifically used to describe a particular domain of knowledge.
fields.label: vocabulary

fields.description: A unit of computer code in source or compiled form, employing one or more algorithms to be executed by a digital computer to undertake a particular task.  Computer programs are collectively called 'software' to distinguish them from the equipment ('hardware') upon which they run.
fields.label: computer program

fields.description: A thesis reporting a research project undertaken as part of a graduate course of education leading to a master's degree.
fields.label: master's thesis

fields.description: A general term for the realization of a work conveying a body of information primarily in textual form. A document may contain one or more figures and tables in addition to text.
fields.label: document

fields.description: A new edition of a historical publication, edited by a scholar other than the original author, containing within the body text the supposedly ‘best’ version of the original work, with footnotes detailing and commenting on textual variations between different versions, with an introduction written by the scholar, and with a bibliography listing related publications.
fields.label: critical edition

fields.description: A news report published in a newspaper issue.
fields.label: newspaper news item

fields.description: A set of metadata elements, policies and guidelines defined for a particular application.  The metadata elements used in the application profile may be drawn from more than one element sets, including locally defined sets.
fields.label: application profile

fields.description: A defined document section, forming part of or intended for inclusion within a larger document, usually with its own title or chapter number.  Different chapters within a document such as a book or a report may each be independently authored, or may all be authored by a single individual or group of authors.
fields.label: chapter

fields.description: A snapshots of (part of) the World Wide Web.
fields.label: web archive

fields.description: A type of service showing regular entries of commentary, descriptions of events, or other material such as images or videos, with the most recent entries commonly displayed in reverse-chronological order.  'Blog' ia a contraction of 'web log'.
fields.label: blog

fields.description: A moving display, either generated dynamically by a computer program or formed from a series of pre-recorded still images imparting an impression of motion when shown in succession.  Examples include animations, cine films, videos, and computational simulations. Expressions of moving images may incorporate synchronized soundtracks.
fields.label: moving image

fields.description: A particular published volume of a journal, comprising one or more journal issues.
fields.label: journal volume

fields.description: A personal record, in a form of book, with discrete entries (often handwritten) arranged by date, reporting what has happened over the course of a day or other period of time.
fields.label: diary

fields.description: A sequence of books having certain characteristics in common that are formally identified together as a group.
fields.label: book series

fields.description: A classification arranged in a hierarchical structure of classes and subclasses, showing parent-child isA relationships, or broader_than - narrower_than relationships.
fields.label: taxonomy

fields.description: A print book bound with rigid protective covers (typically of cardboard covered with cloth, heavy paper, or sometimes leather). They may have flexible sewn spines which allow the book to lie flat on a surface when opened, although most modern commercial hardcover books have glued spines.
fields.label: hardback

fields.description: A report describing a deliverable created or achieved within a specific project.
fields.label: deliverable report

fields.description: A document accompanying a published journal article, containing additional information of relevance to the article, typically available from the publisher's web site via a hyperlink from the journal article itself.
fields.label: supplementary information

fields.description: A piece of writing published in a periodical issue, typically accompanied by other items by different authors.
fields.label: periodical item

fields.description: An explicit description of, or set of requirements to be satisfied by a material, product resource, service or standard.
fields.label: specification

fields.description: A repository for storing documents.
fields.label: document repository

fields.description: Metadata describing the citations made within a work to other works, and (optionally) some characteristics of the expressions of the cited works.
fields.label: citation metadata

fields.description: An instructional document typically supplied with a technologically advanced consumer product, such as a car or a computer application, or with an item of complex equipment such as a microscope.
fields.label: instruction manual

fields.description: An authoritative report or guide designed to educate readers and help people make decisions, or to explain technical problems and how to solve them. White papers are typically published by governments to propose new legislation for discussion, and by commercial companies to inform readers about products or services, as aids to marketing.
fields.label: white paper

fields.description: The version of an author's original scholarly work, such as a research paper or a review, first submitted to a journal for publication.  [Note: For that version of the article resubmitted after peer-review and revision, use fabio:Postprint. For that version published by the journal and forming the 'version of record', use fabio:JournalArticle.  See also fabio:Manuscript]
fields.label: preprint

fields.description: A notebook used by an individual research scientist as the primary record of his or her research activities. A researcher may use a laboratory notebook to document hypotheses, to describe experiments and to record data in various formats, to provide details of data analysis and interpretation, or to record the validation or invalidatiion of the original hypotheses. The laboratory notebook serves as an organizational tool and a memory aid.  It may also have a role in recording and protecting any intellectual property created during the research, and may be used in evidence when establishing priority of discoveries, for example in patent applications.  Electronic versions of laboratory notebooks are increasingly being employed by researchers, particularly in chemistry and the pharmaeutical industry.
fields.label: laboratory notebook

fields.description: A component of the case for support of a grant application, describing a particular aspect of the work to be undertaken.
fields.label: WorkPackage

fields.description: A set of questions on a particular topic designed to test the academic, professional or technical ability of the person taking the examination, with achievement of a pass grade in the examination typically being a prerequisite for the award of an educational award such as a degree, or of a professional or technical qualification.
fields.label: examination paper

fields.description: A particular manifestation collecting other manifestations.
fields.label: manifestation collection

fields.description: The realization of a grant application, usually containing a case for support document.
fields.label: grant application document

fields.description: A formal correction to an error introduced by the publisher into a previously published document, typically published as a journal item in a subsequent issue of the journal, or as a separate loose-leaf sheet inserted into a book.
fields.label: erratum

fields.description: A report of a technical nature.
fields.label: technical report

fields.description: A particular issue of a periodical, identified and distinguished from other issues of the same publication by date and/or issue number and/or volume number, and comprising separate periodical items such as editorials, articles and news items.
fields.label: periodical issue

fields.description: An account of the events, works and achievements, both personal and professional, of a person, either living or dead.
fields.label: biography

fields.description: A formal disclosure of a new invention, made in application for a patent.
fields.label: patent application

fields.description: A scholarly periodical primarily devoted to the publication of original research papers. [Printed and electronic manifestations of the same journal are usually identified by separate print and electronic International Standard Serial Numbers (ISSN or eISSN, respectively), that identifies the journal as a whole, not to individual issues of it.]
fields.label: journal

fields.description: A set of recommendations for the minimum reporting requirements to be employed when reporting a particular type of investigation or project, for example a randomized clinical trial.  A reporting standard may involve a checklist and a flow diagram, offers a standard way for authors to prepare a complete and transparent report of their findings, and aids their critical appraisal and interpretation of their data. [See also fabio:MinimalInformationStandard.]
fields.label: reporting standard

fields.description: The report of a pre-planned medical or veterinary clinical study of the safety, efficacy, or optimum dosage schedule of one or more diagnostic, therapeutic or prophylactic drugs, or of devices, treatments or techniques, involving a randomized controlled trial for evidence-based assessment in humans or animals selected according to predetermined criteria of eligibility and observed for evidence of favourable and unfavourable effects.
fields.label: clinical trial report

fields.description: A subclass of FRBR item, restricted to exemplars of fabio:Manifestations.  An example of a fabio:Item is a printed copy of a journal article on your desk, or a PDF file of that article that you purchased from a publisher and that now resides in digital form on your computer hard drive.
fields.label: item

fields.description: A piece of music exists in the form of a composition in musical notation.
fields.label: musical composition

fields.description: A news report published in a journal issue.
fields.label: journal news item

fields.description: A particular published issue of a journal, one or more of which will constitute a volume of the journal.
fields.label: journal issue

fields.description: A book authored by a student containing a formal presentations of research outputs submitted for examination in completion of a course of study at an institution of higher education, to fulfil the requirements for an academic degree.  Also know as a dissertation.  [For the alternative meaning of the word 'thesis', namely the formulation of a concept, hypothesis, idea, point of view or theory presented for review and/or discussion, use fabio:Proposition.]
fields.label: thesis

fields.description: A manifestation of the expresson of a work in physical printed form, typically on paper.
fields.label: print object

fields.description: The realization of a report, usually in printed form.
fields.label: report document

fields.description: A database specifically disigned for the storage and retrieval of Resource Description Framework (RDF) data consisting of subject-predicate-object triples.  A triple store is queried using the RDF query language SPARQL.
fields.label: triplestore

fields.description: A collection of the literary or scholastic works of a single person.
fields.label: collected works

fields.description: Information prepared specifically and primarily for manifestation in a web page, comprising text, images, datasets and/or other works.
fields.label: web content

fields.description: An article published in a magazine issue.
fields.label: magazine article

fields.description: An electronic form of data storage that displays a grid of rows and columns, in which each editable cell can contain alphanumeric text, a numeric value, or a formula that defines how the content of that cell is to be calculated from the content of another cell or cells.
fields.label: spreadsheet

fields.description: A non-peer reviewed periodical, usually published daily or weekly, consisting primarily of editorials and news items concerning current or recent events and matters of public interest.
fields.label: newspaper

fields.description: An article writen by a journalist and published in a newspaper.
fields.label: newspaper article

fields.description: A work created for the purpose of education or instruction, that may be expressed as a  text book, a lecture, a tutorial or an instruction manual.
fields.label: instructional work

fields.description: A type of controlled vocabulary used in information retrieval applications for indexing or tagging purposes, in which relationships between terms are made explicit. These are normally hierarchical relationships (is-a, subsumption; e.g. a cow is a mammal), equivalency relationships relating non-preferred terms to preferred terms (e.g. pitch and frequency), or associative relationships, in which the relationship that exists is neither one of hierarchy or equivalence, but rather one of similarity (e.g. sports and leisure pursuits).
fields.label: thesaurus

fields.description: In printing and publishing, a proof copy is the preliminary versions of a publication, after the inclusion of any author corrections following review, and after copy editing to bring the manuscript into the house style, intended for final checking prior to publication to detect and eliminate typographical errors, omissions or transpositions of text, incorrect layout or placement of illustrations and tables, or other formatting errors.  Those who check proofs include the editor, possibly the peer-reviewers (to ensure that their requested modifications have been included to their satisfaction), possibly an in-house professional proof-reader, and / or the author, who is ultimately responsible for enduring the published work says what (s)he means it to say.  Substantive changes to the text are not permitted once the manuscript has reached proof stage.
fields.label: proof

fields.description: The realization of an opinion written by an editor.
fields.label: editorial

fields.description: A repository for storing data.
fields.label: data repository

fields.description: A list of items describing the content of a resource, for example items in an exhibition, items offered for sale by a vendor, or entities contained within a library or collection.  Ideally, Catalogs are created according to specific and uniform principles of construction and are under the control of an authority file.
fields.label: catalog

fields.description: A document containing the programme and collected conference papers, or their abstracts, presented at a conference, seminar, symposium, workshop or similar event.
fields.label: conference proceedings

fields.description: A recorded sequence of connected steps, which may be automated, specifying a reliably repeatable sequence of operations to be undertaken when conducting a particular job, for example an in silico investigation that extracts and processes information from a number of bioinformatics databases.
fields.label: workflow

fields.description: A collection of documents, for example a periodical or a book series.
fields.label: document collection

fields.description: A written or printed communication of a personal or professional nature between individuals and/or representatives of corporate bodies, usually transmitted by the postal service or published in a periodical.  In the latter case, the letter is typically addressed to the editor and comments on or discussed an item previously published by that periodical, or of interest to its readership.
fields.label: letter

fields.description: A written review and critical analysis of the content, scope and quality of a book or other monographic work.
fields.label: book review

fields.description: A work of fiction that is usually written in prose, often in narrative format. This format tends to be more pointed than longer works of fiction, such as novels.
fields.label: short story

fields.description: A means of storing information in non-digital form, e.g. paper, film (for analogue photographs or movies), magnetic tape (for analogue sound recordings or video recordings) or vinyl disc.
fields.label: analog storage medium

fields.description: A small computer program written in a scripting language such as JavaScript, PHP or Perl that allows control of one or more software applications.
fields.label: script

fields.description: A mathematical, graphical or physical representation of some physical reality, conceptual idea or theoretical construct.
fields.label: model

fields.description: A computer system in which information may be stored.
fields.label: repository

fields.description: A display poster, typically containing text withillustrative figures and/or tables,  usually reporting research results or proposing hypotheses, submitted for acceptance to and/or presented at a conference, seminar, symposium, workshop or similar event.
fields.label: conference poster

fields.description: A verbal or written remark often related to an added piece of information, or an observation or statement.
fields.label: comment

fields.description: A computer program designed to assist a human user to perform one or more goal-oriented tasks such as word processing or image processing.  A computer application will typically save its output files in one or more specific formats, conforming either to proprietary or open standards.
fields.label: computer application

fields.description: A report of an item of news.
fields.label: news report

fields.description: An article, typically the realization of a research paper reporting original research findings, published in a journal issue.
fields.label: journal article

fields.description: A set of questions on a particular topic, usually providing multiple choice questions or the ability to indicate support for a proposal on a numerical scale, designed for rapid numerical analysis of responses and used in surveying public opinion.
fields.label: questionnaire

fields.description: Metadata describing the project that led to the creation of the work, for example the project name, the name of the institution in which the project was conducted, and project funding information.
fields.label: project metadata

fields.description: A form of literature written by a playwright, usually consisting of scripted dialogue between characters, intended for theatrical performance rather than reading.
fields.label: play

fields.description: A collection of all the literary or scholastic works of a single person.
fields.label: complete works

fields.description: An expression of a personal or professional opinion on an issue or topic.
fields.label: opinion

fields.description: A report of original research findings.
fields.label: research paper

fields.description: A subclass of FRBR expression, restricted to expressions of fabio:Works.  For your latest research paper, Draft 5, the preprint and the published version, to which the publisher assigned a unique digital object identifier, are all expressions of the same work.
fields.label: expression

fields.description: Clear and detailed written instructions of a prescribed step-by-step procedure to be routinely followed, and decisions to be made when undertaking a specific task, process or function, to achieve consistent performance, ensure safety and/or assure data quality.  (Commonly abbreviated 'SOP'.)
fields.label: SOP

fields.description: A scholarly review of others' work.
fields.label: review

fields.description: A collection of selected words and phrases related to a particular domain of knowledge used to permit consistency of metadata annotation and improved retrieval following a search, in which homonyms, synomyms and similar ambiguities of meaning present in natural language are disambiguated.
fields.label: controlled vocabulary

fields.description: A separate work that provides information describing one or more characteristics of a resource or entity.
fields.label: metadata

fields.description: A textual work prepared 'by hand', such as a typescript or word-processed pre-publication draft of a research paper or a report, or a work not otherwise reproduced in multiple copies.  [Note: fabio:Manuscript is not intended to describe a handwritten historical document on paper or parchment, for which the FRBR distinctions between work, expression, manifestation and item (individual copy) becomes blurred.].
fields.label: manuscript

fields.description: A non-defined collection of words and phrases relating to a particular domain of knowledge, usually added freely by a community, in which homonyms, synomyms and similar ambiguities of meaning present in natural language are not formally disambiguated.
fields.label: UncontrolledVocabulary

fields.description: The realization of a moving image.
fields.label: movie

fields.description: A book containing personal notes, typically created by writing into a physical book with blank pages.
fields.label: notebook

fields.description: A brief summary of a work on a particular subject (typically a research paper, report, review or thesis), appearing at the beginning of the work and designed to act as the point-of-entry that will help the reader quickly to obtain an overview of the work's contents.
fields.label: abstract

fields.description: A controlled vocabulary or official list that establishes, for consistency, the authoritative forms of headings, preferred terms or proper names to be used when creating a catalogue, or when indexing and searching a set of entities within a defined domain.
fields.label: authority file

fields.description: A structured collection of logically related records or data usually stored and retrieved using computer-based means.
fields.label: database

fields.description: A document containing notes that summarize a lecture or course of lectures.
fields.label: lecture notes

fields.description: A paper, typically the realization of a research paper reporting original research findings, usually published within a conference proceeding.
fields.label: conference paper

fields.description: A musical composition that contains vocal parts ('lyrics') that are performed ('sung').
fields.label: song

fields.description: A collection of related web pages containing text, images, videos and/ or other digital assets that are addressed relative to a common Uniform Resource Locator (URL), often consisting of only the domain name, or the IP address, and the root path ('/') in an Internet Protocol-based network. A web site is hosted on at least one web server, accessible via a network such as the Internet or a private local area network.
fields.label: Web site

fields.description: A formal factual, methodological, statistical, technical or research report issued by an individual, group, agency, government body or other institution.
fields.label: report

fields.description: A work  to which people refer for authoritative factual information, such as included in a dictionary, encyclopaedia, handbook or field guide, or in certain types of informative web page, such as an institutional, research group or project home page.
fields.label: reference work

fields.description: An item defined by a real object, such as a particular copy of the book 'Alice's adventures in Wonderland' anybody may have on its desk.
fields.label: analog item

fields.description: A system of classification derived from the practice and method of collaboratively creating and managing tags to annotate and categorize content. [Contrast fabio:Ontology]
fields.label: folksonomy

fields.description: A long narrative in literary prose.
fields.label: novel

fields.description: An editorial published in an issue of a journal.
fields.label: journal editorial

fields.description: The realizatrion of a piece of writing on a particular topic.
fields.label: article

fields.description: Information manifested in a blog, one of a set of periodic sequential entries containing commentary, descriptions of events, or other material such as images or videos, usually displayed in reverse-chronological order and usually maintained by an individual.
fields.label: blog entry

fields.description: A part of a grant application that provides a description of a proposed project and gives reasons why it is worthy of funding. (See also fabio:GrantApplication).
fields.label: case for support

fields.description: A visual communication object comprising one or more still images on a related theme.  If included within a publication, a figure is typically unaligned with the main body of text, having its own descriptive textual figure legend.
fields.label: figure

fields.description: A presentation of findings following a clinical or medical investigation on a human or animal patient, that may contain a diagnosis and proposals for therapeutic treatment and/or epidemiological control measures, or may propose further evaluative studies that will eventually lead to such outcomes.
fields.label: clinical case report

fields.description: A metadata standard specifying items to be included when creating metadata describing a dataset of a particular type, or when creating a structured digital abstract summarizing the main findings of an article or report in a particular domain of interest, thereby ensuring adequate descriptive information is recorded for subsequent resource discovery and/or interpretation of the information described.  [See also fabio:ReportingStandard.]
fields.label: minimal information standard

fields.description: A tabular dataset providing information about the times and locations of a planned series of events.
fields.label: timetable

fields.description: The physical or electronic realization of a patent application.
fields.label: patent application document

fields.description: A set of slides containing text, tables or figures, designed to communicate ideas or research results, for projection and viewing by an audience at a conference, symposium, seminar, lecture, workshop or other gatherings, typically embodied in a particular manifestation format such as a SlideShare or PowerPoint slideshow.
fields.label: presentation

fields.description: The version of an author's original scholarly work, such as a research paper or a review, re-submitted for publication after revision by the author in the light of comments from reviewers.  [Note: For the version before peer review, use fabio:Preprint. For the version published by the journal and forming the 'version of record', use fabio:JournalArticle.  See also fabio:Manuscript]
fields.label: postprint

fields.description:
A subclass of FRBR manifestation, restricted to manifestations of fabio:Expressions. fabio:Manifestation specifically applies to electronic (digital) as well as to physical manifestations of expressions.  

Examples of different manifestations of a single 'version of record' expression of a scholarly work include an article in a print journal, the on-line version of that article as an HTML web page, and the downloadable PDF version of the same article, which can be seen as alternate 'containers' or 'channels' for the same information.
fields.label: manifestation

fields.description: A document that contains metadata information describing one or more characteristics of an entity.
fields.label: metadata document

fields.description: A manifestation of the expresson of a work on the World Wide Web, usually structured as an HTML or XHTML computer file, identified by a Uniform Resource Identifier (URI), and made accessible to a user by means of the Hypertext Transport Protocol (HTTP) in a web browser window.  Special software may enable a web page to be or to include a blog or a wiki.  Several interlinked web pages hosted together on a web server and accessed through a single domain name or IP address constitute a web site.
fields.label: Web page

fields.description: A news report published in a magazine issue.
fields.label: magazine news item

fields.description: A particular item collecting other items.
fields.label: item collection

fields.description: An unpublished paper, usually circulated privately among a small group of peers, to provide information or with a request for comments or editorial improvement.
fields.label: working paper

fields.description: A predefined written procedural method, designed to ensure reliability of findings, for undertaking a medical or veterinary clinical study of the safety, efficacy, or optimum dosage schedule of one or more diagnostic, therapeutic or prophylactic drugs or treatments, or of devices or techniques, involving a randomized controlled trial for evidence-based assessment in humans or animals, specifying criteria of eligibility, nature of controls, sampling schedules, data collection parameters, statistical analyses, reporting standards, etc. to be employed in undertaking the clinical trial.
fields.label: clinical trial design

fields.description: A graphical means of presenting data in a grid of rows and columns, within which the cells usually contain alphanumeric text or numeric values.  If included within a publication, a table typically appearing unaligned with the main body of text, with its own descriptive title.
fields.label: table

fields.description: A movie with an accompanying soundtrack, typically created by a professional film studio, designed to communicate a fictional story, record an artistic event, or impart information that is scientific or documentary in nature.
fields.label: film

fields.description: A formal representation of a set of concepts within a domain of knowledge, and the logical relationships between those concepts.  [Contrast fabio:Folksonomy]
fields.label: ontology

fields.description: An item from the controlled vocabulary of a particular classification system, such as the ACM Computing Classification System or MeSH, the Medical Subject Headings, used as an annotation to describe the subject, meaning or content of an entity.
fields.label: annotation category

fields.description: A message transmitted over the internet as an item of electronic mail, typically based on the Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP).  Emails can have computer files containing documents, dataset and images attached to them or embedded within them.
fields.label: e-mail

fields.description: A precise sequential set of pre-defined logical rules or computational operations to be employed for solving a particular problem in a finite number of steps.
fields.label: algorithm

fields.description: An official or public specification of, or requirement for, a technical method, practice, process or protocol that is involved in, for example, manufacturing, computation, electronic communication, or digital media.
fields.label: technical standard

fields.description: A predefined written procedural method, designed to ensure successful replication of results by others in the same or other laboratories, that describes the overall objectives, organization and implementation of a scientific experiment, and specifies the experimental design, experimental methods, reagents, instrumentation, sampling schedules, data collection parameters, statistical analyses, image processing procedures, safety precautions, reporting standards, etc. employed in undertaking the experiment.
fields.label: experimental protocol

fields.description: A computer program that enables a separate computer to interact programmatically with the computer running the API.  (Commonly abbreviated 'API'.)
fields.label: API

fields.description: A subclass of FRBR work, restricted to works that are published or potentially publishable, and that contain or are referred to by bibliographic references, or entities used to define bibliographic references.  FaBiO works are primarily academic publications, but also include legal records, governmental papers, technical and commercial reports and similar publications, and also bibliographies, reference lists, library catalogues and similar collections.   For this reason, fabio:Work is not an equivalent class to frbr:ScholarlyWork.  An example of a fabio:Work is your latest research paper.
fields.label: work

fields.description: A periodical, usually devoted to a particular topic or domain of interest, and usually published weekly or monthly, consisting primarily of  non-peer reviewed editorials, journalistic news items and more substantive articles, reviews, book reviews and discussions concerning current or recent events and publications, and matters of interest to the domain served by the magazine.  [Some scientific journals, notably Science and Nature, also secondarily serve as science magazines by containing substantive editorials and news items on vital or controversial issues].
fields.label: magazine

fields.description: A device for recording information or storing data.
fields.label: storage medium

fields.description: A proposal or proposition of a new conceptualization, hypothesis, idea or theory.
fields.label: proposition

fields.description: A literature review focused on a single question that tries to identify, appraise, select and synthesize all high quality research evidence relevant to that question. Systematic reviews of high-quality randomized controlled trials are crucial to evidence-based medicine. An understanding of systematic reviews and how to implement them in practice is becoming mandatory for all professionals involved in the delivery of health care. Systematic reviews are not limited to medicine,  and are quite common in other sciences such as psychology, educational research and sociology.
fields.label: systematic review

fields.description: The realization of a sound recording.
fields.label: audio document

fields.description: An item defined by a digital object, such as a computer file.
fields.label: digital item

fields.description: A book containing instructional material relating to a particular topic of academic study, designed to be read by students.
fields.label: textbook

fields.description: A thesis reporting the research undertaken during a period of graduate study leading to a doctoral degree.
fields.label: Doctoral thesis

fields.description: A news report published by an organization to provide information to journalists.
fields.label: press release

fields.description: A written work made especially for a film or television program. Screenplays can be original works or adaptations from existing pieces of writing.
fields.label: screenplay

fields.description: A particular published  issue of a newspaper, identified by date, and sometimes also by place or time (e.g. 'Late London Edition').
fields.label: newspaper issue

fields.description: A database of information which is heavily optimized for reading.
fields.label: directory

fields.description: A formal disclosure of a new invention approved by a governmental patent agency, made to register intellectual property rights, and to give exclusive rights to the inventor or assignee to manufacture, use, licence or sell the invention for a certain number of years.
fields.label: patent

fields.description: A role some agents may have.
fields.label: role

fields.description: A particular situation that describe a role some agents may have at a particular time.
fields.label: role in time

fields.description: A particular situation that describe a state or condition some documents may have at a particular time as consequece of one or more events.
fields.label: status in time

fields.description: An entity, such as a person, a group, an organization, a software agent, involved in one or more events.
fields.label: agent

fields.description: A state or condition some documents may have.
fields.label: status

fields.description: A sequence of connected steps, representing a sequence of publishing operations undertaken by agents. A workflow may be seen as an abstract model of real work.
fields.label: workflow

fields.description: An atomic unit of a workflow, that may be characterized by a starting time and an ending time, and may be associated with one or more events.  A workflow step usually involves some input information, material or energy needed to complete the step, and some output information, material or energy produced by that step.  In the case of a publishing workflow, a step typically results in the creation of a publication entity, usually by the modification of another pre-existing publication entity, e.g. the creation of an edited paper from a rough draft, or of an HTML representation from an XML mark-up.
fields.label: step

fields.description: Defines the effort expended in making a contribution.
fields.label: contribution effort

fields.description: Defines the type or nature of a contribution made with respect to the authorship of a publication such as a journal article.  Individual members of this class are used to specify particular authorship contributions.
fields.label: authorship contribution

fields.description: A computer system or software program whose action has an effect on external events, for example a laboratory robot that undertakes your experiments, or the financial control system that controls an institution's payrole, or that, following programmed business rules, prevents the principal investigator from placing an order for research equipment because there is insufficient money left in the project budget.
fields.label: computational agent

fields.description: The situation an agent has of making a contribution to realizing a goal or completing a task relating to a scholarly activity or entity such as journal article.  The type or nature of the contribution is defined by the object of the object property scoro:withContribution, which is an individual in the class scoro:Contribution or one of its sub-classes.  The entity to which the contribution relates is specified using the object property scoro:relatesToEntity or one of its sub-properties, and the effort expended in making that contribution is specified using the object property scoro:withContributionEffort.
fields.label: contribution situation

fields.description: Defines the type or nature of an organizational or administrative contribution.  Individual members of this class are used to specify particular contributions.
fields.label: organizational contribution

fields.description: A role that an agent might hold with respect to an organization and its administration, particularly within an academic context.  Individual members of this class are used to specify particular roles.
fields.label: organizational role

fields.description: A role that a person might hold as an author of a publication or the creator of a work.  Individual members of this class are used to specify particular roles.
fields.label: authorship role

fields.description: A role that an agent might hold with respect to data.  Individual members of this class are used to specify particular roles.
fields.label: data role

fields.description: A role that an agent might hold with respect to an educational organization or activity.  Individual members of this class are used to specify particular educational roles.
fields.label: educational role

fields.description: Defines the type or nature of a contribution made by an agent.  Individual members of this class or its sub-classes are used to specify particular contributions.
fields.label: contribution

fields.description: Defines the type or nature of a practical or experimental contribution made to the research.  Individual members of this class are used to specify particular contributions.
fields.label: experimental contribution

fields.description: A role that an agent might hold with respect to a project.  Individual members of this class are used to specify particular roles.
fields.label: project role

fields.description: Defines the type or nature of an intellectual contribution made to the research described in a journal article.  Individual members of this class are used to specify particular contributions.
fields.label: intellectual contribution

fields.description: A role that an agent might hold with respect to an investigation.  Individual members of this class are used to specify particular roles.
fields.label: investigation role

fields.description: A role that an agent might hold with respect to academic and project finance.  Individual members of this class are used to specify particular roles.
fields.label: financial role

fields.description: A review of an work
fields.label: Review

fields.description: Feedback on the review. Expresses whether the review was useful or not
fields.label: Feedback

fields.description: A comment on a review
fields.label: Comment

fields.description: A Position which involes portraying a Character.
fields.label: Portrayal

fields.description: An event which involves preparatory work for a Performance.
fields.label: Rehersal

fields.description: The realisation of a theatrical work.
fields.label: Production

fields.description: An event which involves participation, mainly with an educational focus.
fields.label: Workshop

fields.description: An Organisation which puts on Productions.
fields.label: ProductionCompany

fields.description: An event which involves discussion/planning, often with a formal tone.
fields.label: Meeting

fields.description: The writing/devising which may enable a Production.
fields.label: Show

fields.description: A performance which reviewers are encouraged to attend.
fields.label: PressNight

fields.description: The voice classification for a Singer or singing part.
fields.label: Voice

fields.description: A Provision which makes an ev:Event more accessible
fields.label: AccessibilityProvision

fields.description: A Nestable Spatial Thing used for Theatrical Events.
fields.label: Venue

fields.description: A set of responibilities.
fields.label: Position

fields.description: An unpolished performance in which the cast read from scripts.
fields.label: RehersalReading

fields.description: A collection of Productions and/or Performances
fields.label: Season

fields.description: A Project which intends to evoke a response from an Audience.
fields.label: PerformableProject

fields.description: A ticket placeholder is a dummy for multiple tickets that are themselves not exposed as data.
fields.label: TicketPlaceholder (gr:ProductOrService)

fields.description:
The class of qualitative values indicating a seat position (e.g. the seat 4B in a given plane) or a seat category (e.g. window seat). 
    Note that the same vessel or building may have multiple seating layouts.
fields.label: SeatOrSeatCategory (gr:QualitativeValue)

fields.description:
A service to transport passengers or cargo from one location to another location, with optionally intermediate stops

Note: By design, the Tickets Ontology does not provide mechanisms for modeling rules for recurring patterns of transportation services (e.g. every Monday at 8:00). Instead, it expects that you materialize each individual connection on a given day.
Most timetable applications are complex databases, so they will have to be exposed as SPARQL endpoints anyway.
fields.label: TransportationService

fields.description: A regular or individual service to transport passengers or cargo from one location to another location by means of a coach or bus.
fields.label: CoachService

fields.description: An actual ticket is single, identifiable right to access a particular event, location, or transportation service.
fields.label: ActualTicket (gr:ProductOrService)

fields.description: This is a conceptual entity that collates all properties defining the type of access a ticket provides to a particular event, location, or transportation.
fields.label: ScopeOfAccess

fields.description:
The class of qualitative values indicating a discount type, audience, or group type - e.g. students, military personnel, etc.

Note: Discount types that solely represent age ranges (e.g. children, senior citizens, ...) are better expressed using tio:ageRange.
fields.label: DiscountType (gr:QualitativeValue)

fields.description:
A regular or individual service to transport passengers or cargo from one location to another location by means of a train, subway, or other railroad vehicle

Note: By design, the Tickets Ontology does not provide mechanisms for modeling rules for recurring patterns of transportation services (e.g. every Monday at 8:00). Instead, it expects that you materialize each individual connection on a given day.
Most train schedule applications are complex databases, so they will have to be exposed as SPARQL endpoints anyway.
fields.label: TrainService

fields.description: A seating layout for a particular location, vessel, or single transportation service
fields.label: SeatingLayout

fields.description:
The initial, final, or any intermediate point in time and space of a particular tio:TransportationService, 
characterized by its location (tio:at), arrival time (tio:arrives), and departure time (tio:departs). 
Each tio:TransportationService has at least one tio:Stop for the point and time of departure and another one for the final destination.
fields.label: Stop

fields.description:
A point or area of interest, e.g. a museum, a train station, an airport, a bus stop, a store, a box office, etc.

Note 1: Use existing vocabularies like vcard or geo to attach address and geoposition (lat/long) details to the location.
Note 2: You can safely re-use any existing location, area, or point of interest from other data sources, e.g. DBPedia.
fields.label: POI (gr:LocationOfSalesOrServiceProvisioning)

fields.description:
A regular or individual service to transport passengers or cargo from one location to another location by means of an aircraft

Note: By design, the Tickets Ontology does not provide mechanisms for modeling rules for recurring patterns of transportation services (e.g. every Monday at 8:00). Instead, it expects that you materialize each individual connection on a given day.
Most flight schedule applications are complex databases, so they will have to be exposed as SPARQL endpoints anyway.
fields.label: Flight

fields.description: The class of qualitative values indicating a service level oder fare class (e.g. Business Class).
fields.label: ServiceLevel (gr:QualitativeValue)

fields.description: A ticket is a tradeable right to access a particular event or location, or to use a particular transportation service.
fields.label: Ticket (gr:ProductOrService)

fields.description:
An event, e.g. a concert, a show, etc. You can also safely use the following external classes for describing the respective event:

http://linkedevents.org/ontology/Event (lode:Event)
http://purl.org/NET/c4dm/event.owl#Event (event:Event)
http://www.loa-cnr.it/ontologies/DUL.owl#Event (dul:Event)

Note: You can attach the time and date of the event using tio:starts and tio:ends as simple datatype properties, even if lode:Event and event:Event recommend other, more sophisticated ways of modeling the temporal aspects of events.
fields.label: Event

fields.description: A taxi service to transport passengers from one location to another location
fields.label: Taxi

fields.description: The conceputal representation of anything that is a property (a thing that is inherent in an entity, like eye color) or an attribute (a thing that has been assigned, or attributed, to an entity, like name or identification number).
fields.label: Quality

fields.description:
Universal (natural) sets of objects, processes, qualities, states, 
etc. in reality (for example on the side of the patient); (from http://ontology.buffalo.edu/bfo/Terminology_for_Ontologies.pdf)
fields.label: Universal Class

fields.description: A concept representing the relationship between two independent entities.
fields.label: Relation

fields.description: An abstract or general idea inferred or derived from specific instances, representing a set of those instances.
fields.label: Type

fields.description: Relationships in reality. (from http://ontology.buffalo.edu/bfo/Terminology_for_Ontologies.pdf)
fields.label: Universal Relation

fields.description:
Entities that describe the objects, processes, qualities, states, 
etc. in reality (for example on the side of the patient); (from http://ontology.buffalo.edu/bfo/Terminology_for_Ontologies.pdf)
fields.label: Universal

fields.description: Asserts owl:sameAs relationships between resources and external URIs based on the instances' values of a specific property and their interpretation by a mapping specified by conversion:linksVia. How this mapping is performed based on this value is unspecified, but may be based on aligning with (e.g. SKOS) labels or the edit distance between the property value and instances in a known ontology.
fields.label: Object sameAs enahncements
The state of a document at a point in time.

fields.description: A shell script that sets https://github.com/timrdf/csv2rdf4lod-automation/wiki/CSV2RDF4LOD-environment-variables to control the behavior of csv2rdf4lod-automation.
fields.label: CSV2RDF4LOD_environment_variables

fields.description: Omit triple if there is no value in the cell of the given column.
fields.label: Only if column

fields.description: A conversion:Dataset whose data skeleton is available from a version control system.
fields.label: VersionControlledDataset
A raw conversion process from CSV to RDF

fields.description: Casts raw literal values into xsd:boolean datatyped values. The default recognized lexical representations are (case insensitive): 'yes', 'no', 'true', 'false', '0', and '1'. The conversion:boolean_true and conversion:boolean_false properties may be used to add additional lexical forms.
fields.label: Boolean promotion enhancement

fields.description: Reasserts the property-value pair to belong to the existing resource specified by the conversion:bundled_by property.
fields.label: Existing bundle enhancement

fields.description: Omit all triples from this column.
fields.label: Omitted

fields.description: Casts raw literal values into W3CDTF values typed as xsd:date based on a strftime pattern specified with the conversion:date_pattern. If the property values follow different patterns, multiple conversion:date_pattern values may specified.
fields.label: Date promotion enhancement

fields.description: Any SymbolInterpretation that interprets to true or false is a BooleanSymbolInterpretation.
fields.label: Boolean Symbol Interpretation

fields.description: Superclass of enhancements which promote values from a plain literal to a resource.
fields.label: Resource promotion enhancement

fields.description: Reasserts the property-value pair to belong to a new resource specified by the conversion:bundled_by property. An example of this enhancement would be the introduction of a geo:Point instance based on latitude and longitude properties.
fields.label: Implicit bundle enhancement

fields.description: A conversion of a VersionedDataset using a particular set of conversion parameters.
fields.label: Layer Dataset

The superclass of all enhancements. When the enhancement is referring to a particular property, the property's local name or originating column number may be used (using conversion:property_name and ov:csvCol, respectively).

fields.description: An RDF Graph of resources with identifiers (dcterms:identifer, etc) that is used to link to resources created during conversion.
fields.label: LOD Links

fields.description: Repeat value of last non-empty cell in this column for the current cell.
fields.label: Repeat previous if empty column

fields.description: An Enhancement that modifies the subject of the resulting triple.
fields.label: SubjectEnhancement

fields.description: Converts raw literal values into URIs by replacing in the template (specified by the conversion:template_pattern property) the substring '[value]'.
fields.label: Template resource promotion enhancement

fields.description: Promotes the raw literal value to a datatyped literal using the datatype specified with the conversion:range property.
fields.label: Literal datatype promotion enhancement

fields.description: Dataset with source and dataset identifiers, but not version. Before any version is materialized (captured in time), and the union of all VersionedDatasets.
fields.label: Abstract Dataset

fields.description: Refer to a local URI, which then has a single owl:sameAs triple pointing to external LOD bubbles. Depends on owl:sameAs inference OR extra graph patterns in SPARQL queries.
fields.label: IndirectSameAsEnhancement

fields.description: A person, organization, or agent from which a dataset is retrieved.
fields.label: Source

fields.description: Appends raw literal values to the dataset-property-specific value space URI. For example, the value 'AK' for property 'origin_state' would be promoted to </source/SSS/dataset/DDD/value/origin_state/AK>.
fields.label: Property-scoped resource promotion enhancement

fields.description: An Enhancement that modifies the object of the resulting triple.
fields.label: ObjectEnhancement
