fields.description: Metadata for a dataset that is created during the dataset's conversion invocation.
fields.label: ConversionMetaDataset

fields.description: A CatalogedDataset is any kind of dataset, in the most general sense and regardless of how it is encoded (RDF, Relational, Tabular, XML, SPS, etc.). If someone says to you, 'yea, NASA has a Mars imagery dataset, talk to Joe about it and visit its homepage', you just instantiated a CatalogedDataset. There are MANY CatalogedDatasets that are NOT conversion:Datasets and NOT void:Datasets, since both of these are RDF-based datasets. The purpose of CatalogedDataset is to maintain a list of 'TODO' items that could be explored, converted, and published as RDF. Once a CatalogedDataset IS investigated, named, and converted, it also becomes a conversion:Dataset (and thus a void:Datast).
fields.label: Cataloged Dataset

fields.description: In csv2rdf4lod-automation, the conversion trigger is a shell script situated within the conversion cockpit that initiates conversion of source data to RDF.
fields.label: ConversionTrigger

fields.description: Asserts owl:sameAs relationships based on the values in the mapping of the property specified by conversion:subject_of.
fields.label: Subject sameAs enahncements via Lookup

fields.description: Asserts owl:sameAs relationships between instances and external URIs based on the instances' values of a specific property and their interpretation by a mapping specified by conversion:linksVia. How this mapping is performed based on this value is unspecified, but may be based on aligning with (e.g. SKOS) labels or the edit distance between the property value and instances in a known ontology.
fields.label: Subject sameAs enahncements

fields.description: An Enhancement that modifies the predicate of the resulting triple.
fields.label: PredicateEnhancement

fields.description: Cites a row that contains an exemplary resource or structure; 'highlighting' it for increased attention. e.g., Jim Hendler or Bill O'Reilly in a White House Visitor Record.
fields.label: ExampleResource

fields.description: Done by pcurl.sh
fields.label: HTTP Header

fields.description: Asserts that the subject instance is of a specific type, specified by name with conversion:domain_name. Also asserts that the type is a owl:Class.
fields.label: Subject type enhancement

fields.description: Casts raw literal values into W3CDTF values typed as xsd:dateTime based on a strftime pattern specified with the conversion:datetime_pattern. If the property values follow different patterns, multiple conversion:datetime_pattern values may specified. The first matching pattern (of a nondeterministic ordering) will be applied. An optional conversion:datetime_timezone may be specified if no timezone information is present in the datetime pattern.
fields.label: DateTime promotion enhancement

fields.description: A materialized (captured in time) dataset -- something is now on disk. Union of all LayerDatasets created by different conversion parameters.
fields.label: Versioned Dataset

fields.description: Prevents triples with objects of a certain value. Prevents values specified by rdf:value.
fields.label: Interpreted As Null Enhancement

fields.description: Asserts that an existing class in the dataset, specified by name with conversion:class_name,  is a subclass of an external class specified by conversion:subclass_of. This enhancement will materialize the rdf:type entailments for all instances.
fields.label: Subclass enhancement

fields.description: Casts raw literal values directly into a URI.
fields.label: Resource cast enhancement

fields.description: http://www.w3.org/TR/sparql11-service-description/ does not specify a range, but we want to refer to it
fields.label: Service Endpoint

fields.description: add a predicate-object description to the subject of a triple created.
fields.label: SubjectAnnotation

fields.description: A dataset that lists other datasets as its entries.
fields.label: Dataset Catalog

fields.description: UnitTestedDatasets should cite locations for their unit tests.
fields.label: UnitTestedDatset

fields.description: A potentially incomplete subset of a void:Dataset
fields.label: Dataset Sample

fields.description: Ignore string case when attempting to match identifiers between the input table and the identifiers in the LODLinks graph
fields.label: Case Insensitive LOD Link

fields.description: Used to denote that the value of a cell is 'large', where 'large' is loosely defined by the implementing system. For example, javacsv thinks 100,000 characters is Large and requires a setting to permit more than that.
fields.label: LargeValue

fields.description: Represents the structural template for an implicit bundle enhancement. The conversion:property_name specifies the property name by which a bundle is attached to an instance. An optional conversion:type_name may be specified for the bundle to indicate the rdf:type of the new resource.
fields.label: Implicit Bundle
An enhancement of an RDF dataset that adds new RDF triples

fields.description: Constructs a URI from the concatenation of a dataset-specific URI, a type token specified with conversion:range_name, and the raw literal value. Additionally asserts an rdf:type for the new resource with the class named with conversion:range_name. The type name will be lowercased for use in the URI and have the first letter uppercased for use as the class name. For example, the value 'AK' with conversion:range_name 'state' would be promoted to </source/SSS/dataset/DDD/type/state/AK> with an rdf:type of </source/SSS/dataset/DDD/vocab/State>.
fields.label: Typed resource promotion enhancement

fields.description: Asserts that an existing property in the dataset is a subproperty of an external property specified by conversion:subproperty_of. This enhancement will materialize the subproperty entailments for all instances.
fields.label: Subproperty enhancement

fields.description: For any Resource that became owl:sameAs another Resource in an external LOD bubble, use ALL external URIs instead of the local resource.
fields.label: IndirectSameAsEnhancement

fields.description: Renames an existing property in the dataset.
fields.label: Label Rename Enhancement

fields.description: Pairs a collection of symbols with how they should be interpreted. For example, 'S' should be interpreted as http://dbpedia.org/resource/United_States_Senate.
fields.label: SymbolInterpretation

fields.description: Asserts owl:sameAs relationships based on the values in the mapping of the property specified by conversion:subject_of.
fields.label: Object sameAs enahncements via Lookup

fields.description: Data about another Dataset. Can contain VoID, PML, OPM, provenance, Dublin Core, etc.
fields.label: Meta Dataset

fields.description: Any enhnacment with a conversion:links_via can also be a conversion:IncludesLODLinks. When so, include the LODLinks graph in the converted output.
fields.label: Includes LOD Links

fields.description: Uses the object of the conversion:comment property and asserts it as the value of rdfs:comment on the property definition. The value of conversion:comment typically comes from the original csv header (that was too long), or from an ancillary file accompanying the csv file.
fields.label: Property comment enhancement

fields.description: Asserted by pcurl.sh
fields.label: Curl

fields.description: After datatype promotion to an XSD numeric type, multiplies the value by the multiplicand specified with the conversion:multiplier property.
fields.label: Multiplier enhancement

fields.description: Asserted by the converter.
fields.label: Dataset

fields.description: A damage or accident is an event in which the vehicle is being damaged.
fields.label: Damage or Accident

fields.description: An ownership information node is a structured value representing information about the period of ownership of a vehicle by a person or organisation.
fields.label: Ownership Info

fields.description: A type of parking for a vehicle, e.g. in a garage, on the street (open-sky), or in a carport. You can use DBpedia URIs for additional types.
fields.label: Parking Type

fields.description:
A species, typically a pet, for indicating the type of animals that were regularly transported in the vehicle. 

If possible, use DBPedia URIs, e.g. http://dbpedia.org/resource/Dog.
fields.label: Species

fields.description: A type of usage of a vehicle, e.g. rental, taxi, driving school, commuting. It is best to either use one of the predefined individuals or DBpedia URIs whenever possible.
fields.label: Usage Type

fields.description:
A modification or maintenance is an event in which a part of the vehicle is being replaced or removed, or a new part is being added.
Typical examples are the replacement of the engine or the installation of a trailor-hitch.
fields.label: Modification or Maintenance

fields.description: A mandatory or optional technical inspection, e.g. the MOT, a vendor-specific certification of used cars, etc.
fields.label: Check

fields.description: A property-value is a structured value for representing a feature of a vehicle in a semi-formal way.
fields.label: Property Value

fields.description: Represents a ranking score associated with an item.
fields.label: rank

fields.description: A feature of a vrank:Algorithm such as Granularity, RankingFactor, etc.
fields.label: feature

fields.description: A ranking algorithm used to compute the ranking scores associated with an item (vrank:Rank).
fields.label: algorithm

fields.description: A parameter of a vrank:Algorithm such as number of iterations or damping factor.
fields.label: parameter

fields.description: A Center is an OrganisationalUnit that represents a group of people recognised by an OrganisationalUnit as forming a cohesive group referred to by the organisation as a center.
fields.label: Center

fields.description: A Faculty is an OrganisationalUnit that represents a group of people recognised by an OrganisationalUnit as forming a cohesive group referred to by the organisation as a faculty.
fields.label: Faculty

fields.description: A Programme is a KnowledgeGrouping that represents a cohesive collection of educational material referred to by the owning OrganisationalUnit as a programme.
fields.label: Programme

fields.description: A Division is an OrganisationalUnit that represents a group of people recognised by an OrganisationalUnit as forming a cohesive group referred to by the organisation as a division.
fields.label: Division

fields.description: An Insitution is an OrganisationalUnit that represents the upper most level of an academic institution.
fields.label: Institution

fields.description: An Institute is an OrganisationalUnit that represents a group of people recognised by an OrganisationalUnit as forming a cohesive group referred to by the organisation as an institute.
fields.label: Institute

fields.description: A Department is an OrganisationalUnit that represents a group of people recognised by an OrganisationalUnit as forming a cohesive group referred to by the organisation as a department.
fields.label: Department

fields.description: A Course is a KnowledgeGrouping that represents a cohesive collection of educational material referred to by the owning OrganisationalUnit as a course.
fields.label: Course

fields.description: A Subject is a KnowledgeGrouping that represents a cohesive collection of educational material referred to by the owning OrganisationalUnit as a subject.
fields.label: Subject

fields.description: A KnowledgeGrouping represents a collection of resources, learning objectives, timetables, and other materials. The more specific subclasses of Subject, Programme, Course and Module are preferred.
fields.label: KnowledgeGrouping

fields.description: An OrganisationalUnit is used to describe a group of people that form a part of an organisations insitutional hierarchy. More specific classes of Institution, Department, Faculty, School, College, Center, Division and Institute exist and are preferred.
fields.label: Organisational Unit

fields.description: A Module is a KnowledgeGrouping that represents a cohesive collection of educational material referred to by the owning OrganisationalUnit as a module.
fields.label: Module

fields.description: A College is an OrganisationalUnit that represents a group of people recognised by an OrganisationalUnit as forming a cohesive group referred to by the organisation as a college.
fields.label: College

fields.description: A School is an OrganisationalUnit that represents a group of people recognised by an OrganisationalUnit as forming a cohesive group referred to by the organisation as a school.
fields.label: School

fields.description: A death event.
fields.label: Death

fields.description: A general event, i.e. something that the person participated in.
fields.label: Event

fields.description: A marriage event.
fields.label: Marriage

fields.description: A birth event.
fields.label: Birth

fields.description: This class represents any of the FRBR group three entities.
fields.label: subject

fields.description: This class corresponds to the FRBR group one entity 'Expression'.
fields.label: expression

fields.description: This class corresponds to the FRBR group three entity 'Concept'.
fields.label: concept

fields.description: This class represents any of the FRBR group two entities.
fields.label: responsible entity

fields.description: This class corresponds to the FRBR group three entity 'Object'.
fields.label: object

fields.description: This class corresponds to the FRBR group one entity 'Manifestation'.
fields.label: manifestation

fields.description: This class corresponds to the FRBR group two entity 'Corporate Body'.
fields.label: corporate body

fields.description: This class corresponds to the FRBR group two entity 'Person'.
fields.label: person

fields.description: This class represents any one of the FRBR group one entities.
fields.label: endeavour

fields.description: This class corresponds to the FRBR group one entity 'Item'.
fields.label: item

fields.description: This class corresponds to the FRBR group one entity 'Work'.
fields.label: work

fields.description: This class corresponds to the FRBR group three entity 'Place'.
fields.label: place

fields.description: This class corresponds to the FRBR group three entity 'Event'.
fields.label: event

fields.description: A referential work is one which has little meaning when not studied in conjunction with the work it refers to.
fields.label: referential work

fields.description: A referential expression is one which has little meaning when not studied in conjunction with the expression it refers to.
fields.label: referential expression

fields.description: A lifecycle is a series of states connected by allowable transitions. It may be used to describe the lifecycle of business objects or equally the lifecycle of a butterfly.
fields.label: Lifecycle

fields.description: Represents a collection of tasks grouped together for convenience
fields.label: Task Group

fields.description: A transition describes the way in which a resource moves from one state to another state and may also describe the tasks required to make that transition.
fields.label: Transition

fields.description: A state describes one possible state that a resource can be in at a given time. Resources may be in one state in a given lifecycle at any given time, states are considered mutually exclusive within a lifecycle.
fields.label: State

fields.description: Represents a task in a workflow
fields.label: Task

fields.description: Represents an instance of a task taking place against a given resource
fields.label: Action

fields.description: A motorized bicycle is a bicycle with an attached motor used to power the vehicle, or to assist with pedaling.
fields.label: Motorized bicycle (gr:ProductOrService)

fields.description: A value indicating a steering position
fields.label: Steering position value (the class of predefined values)

fields.description: A rickshaw (or ricksha) is a two-wheeled cart which seats one or two persons and is being drawn by a runner.
fields.label: Rickshaw (gr:ProductOrService)

fields.description:
A value indicating a type of fuel.
 
You can safely use any reasonable DBPedia URI, e.g. 
  http://dbpedia.org/resource/Gasoline
  http://dbpedia.org/resource/Diesel
  http://dbpedia.org/resource/Biodiesel
  http://dbpedia.org/resource/Kerosene
fields.label: Fuel type value (the class of predefined values)

fields.description: A canoe (American English) or Canadian canoe (British English) is a small narrow boat, typically human-powered, though it may also be powered by sails or small electric or gas motors.
fields.label: Canoe (gr:ProductOrService)

fields.description: A vehicle is a device that is designed or used to transport people or cargo over land, water, air, or through space.
fields.label: Vehicle (gr:ProductOrService)

fields.description: A kayak is a small human-powered watercraft that traditionally has a covered deck, and one or more cockpits, each seating one paddler who strokes a double-bladed paddle. In this ontology, kayaks are considered watercrafts of their own kind, not a subtype of vso:Boat.
fields.label: Kayak (gr:ProductOrService)

fields.description:
A value indicating an engine type.

You can safely use any reasonable DBPedia URI, e.g. 
  http://dbpedia.org/resource/Two-stroke_engine
  http://dbpedia.org/resource/Four-stroke_engine
  http://dbpedia.org/resource/Wankel_engine
  http://dbpedia.org/resource/Electric_motor
fields.label: Engine type value (the class of predefined values)

fields.description: A value indicating which roadwheels will receive torque
fields.label: Drive wheel configuration value (the class of predefined values)

fields.description: A boat is a watercraft of modest size designed to float or plane, to provide passage across water.
fields.label: Boat (gr:ProductOrService)

fields.description: A value indicating an amount of fuel
fields.label: FuelQuantity

fields.description: A quadracycle is a four-wheeled human-powered vehicle. It is also referred to as a quadricycle, quadcycle pedal car or four-wheeled bicycle.
fields.label: Quadracycle (gr:ProductOrService)

fields.description: A value indicating a speed interval, mostly for explaining vso:acceleration data
fields.label: SpeedInterval

fields.description:
A value indicating a type of transmission.

You can safely use any reasonable DBPedia URI, e.g. 
  http://dbpedia.org/resource/Manual_transmission
  http://dbpedia.org/resource/Automatic_transmission
fields.label: Transmission type value (the class of predefined values)

fields.description: An automobile, motor car, or car is a wheeled motor vehicle used for transporting passengers, which also carries its own engine or motor.
fields.label: Automobile (gr:ProductOrService)

fields.description: A watercraft is a vehicle, vessel or craft designed to move across or through water.
fields.label: Watercraft (gr:ProductOrService)

fields.description: A motorboat is a boat which is powered by an engine.
fields.label: Motor boat (gr:ProductOrService)

fields.description: A sailboat or sailing boat is a boat propelled partly or entirely by sails.
fields.label: Sailing boat (gr:ProductOrService)

fields.description: A lorry (British English) or truck (American English) is a motor vehicle designed to transport cargo.
fields.label: Truck (gr:ProductOrService)

fields.description: A ship is a large watercraft that floats on water.
fields.label: Ship (gr:ProductOrService)

fields.description: A motorized road vehicle is a wheeled land vehicle whose main propulsion is provided by an engine or motor.
fields.label: Motorized road vehicle (gr:ProductOrService)

fields.description: A bicycle or bike is a pedal-driven, human-powered, single-track vehicle, having two wheels attached to a frame, one behind the other. Some bicycles have a small combustion or electric engine that assists with the pedaling.
fields.label: Bicycle (gr:ProductOrService)

fields.description:
A value indicating the an emission standard.

You can safely use any reasonable DBPedia URI, e.g. 
  http://dbpedia.org/resource/Super_Ultra_Low_Emission_Vehicle
  http://dbpedia.org/resource/Partial_zero-emissions_vehicle

See also http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emissions_standard.

Unfortunately, there are no DBPedia identifiers for the popular Euro 1 - Euro 5 standards available.
If you cannot find a suitable identifier in DBPedia, define your own as an instance of vso:EmissionStandardValue.
fields.label: Emission standard value (the class of predefined values)

fields.description: A motorcycle or motorbike is a single-track, two-wheeled motor vehicle.
fields.label: Motorcycle (gr:ProductOrService)

fields.description:
A van is a kind of vehicle used for transporting  goods or groups of people. It is usually a box-shaped vehicle on four wheels, about the same width and length as a large automobile, 
but taller and usually higher off the ground, also referred to as a light commercial vehicle or LCV.
fields.label: Van (gr:ProductOrService)

fields.description:
A bus (also omnibus or autobus) is a road vehicle designed to carry passengers. Buses have a capacity as high as 300 passengers and are widely used for public transportation. 
Coaches are luxury busses, usually in service for long distance travel.
fields.label: Bus or coach (gr:ProductOrService)

fields.description:
A value indicating the features or accessories that are attached to or belong to a vehicle.

You can safely use any reasonable DBPedia URI, e.g. 
  http://dbpedia.org/resource/Anti-lock_braking_system
  http://dbpedia.org/resource/Electronic_stability_control
  http://dbpedia.org/resource/Armrest
  http://dbpedia.org/resource/Spoiler_%28automotive%29
  http://dbpedia.org/resource/CD_Changer
  http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cup_holder
  http://dbpedia.org/resource/Tow_hitch
  http://dbpedia.org/resource/Power_window
  http://dbpedia.org/resource/Power_steering
  http://dbpedia.org/resource/Air_conditioner
  http://dbpedia.org/resource/Child_safety_lock
  http://dbpedia.org/resource/Parking_sensors
fields.label: Feature value (the class of predefined values)

fields.description:
A value indicating the body style of a vehicle.

You can safely use any reasonable DBPedia URI, e.g. 
  http://dbpedia.org/resource/Convertible
  http://dbpedia.org/resource/Hatchback
  http://dbpedia.org/resource/Station_wagon
  http://dbpedia.org/resource/Sport_utility_vehicle
  http://dbpedia.org/resource/Roadster
fields.label: Body style value (the class of predefined values)

fields.description: A value indicating a gearbox type.
fields.label: Gearbox type value (the class of predefined values)

fields.description: The class of engines as choices or components
fields.label: Engine Choice or Component

fields.description: The class of all automatic transmission types
fields.label: TransmissionTypeValueAutomatic

fields.description: The class of paint choices or components (a "MonoSelectGroup" in automotive terminology), VW ID: 3
fields.label: Paint Choice or Component

fields.description: The class of parking-related choices or components (a "MonoSelectGroup" in automotive terminology), VW ID: 7
fields.label: Parking Choice or Component

fields.description: The class of wheels-related choices or components (a "MonoSelectGroup" in automotive terminology), VW ID: 2
fields.label: Wheels Choice or Component

fields.description: The class of upholstery choices or components (a "MonoSelectGroup" in automotive terminology), VW ID: 4
fields.label: Upholstery Choice or Component

fields.description: The class of steering wheels choices or components (a "MonoSelectGroup" in automotive terminology), VW ID: 6
fields.label: Steering Wheels Choice or Component

fields.description: An instance of this class is the specification of a payment option via staged payments.
fields.label: Financing (gr:PaymentMethod)

fields.description: The class of all manual transmission types
fields.label: TransmissionTypeValueManual

fields.description: The class of decorative trim choices or components (a "MonoSelectGroup" in automotive terminology), VW ID: 8
fields.label: Decorative Trims Choice or Component

fields.description: The class of seat-related choices or components (a "MonoSelectGroup" in automotive terminology), VW ID: 9
fields.label: Seats Choice or Component

fields.description: The class of roof choices or components (a "MonoSelectGroup" in automotive terminology), VW ID: 5
fields.label: Roofs Choice or Component

fields.description: A service or service model. Typical instances are complementing services for a particular car.
fields.label: Service

fields.description: The class of audio and navigation choices or components (CD/DVD/SatNav, a "MonoSelectGroup" in automotive terminology), VW ID: 1
fields.label: Audio and Navigation Choice or Component

fields.description: A value indicating a traffic pattern, to be used as a reference for vso:fuelConsumption or vso:fuelEconomy
fields.label: Traffic pattern value (the class of predefined values)

fields.description: A profile represents a particular person playing a given role. In the literature it is also known as a "qua-individual". WAI extends the meaning of profile to capture "person-as-role", "person-at-context" and "person-in-community".
fields.label: Profile

fields.description: A property that can be predicated of a person. In WAI ontology, roles are reified as first order individuals and relations between roles and players are expressed by means of the wai:plays property. WAI does not impose any subclassification of roles. The concept is open to be refined according to domain or application requirements.
fields.label: Role

fields.description: Contexts are similar to situations or state of affairs providing interpretation coordinates for profiles. In the most simple case, these coordinates are just geographical/spatial or temporal coordinates. WAI does not impose a fixed definition of context. It is deliberately wide in order to enable third-parties the adequation of the meaning of context according to their modeling needs and requirements.
fields.label: Context

fields.description: A hierarchical discription of a metabolic pathway.
fields.label: Pathway

fields.description: Warning about possible errors and/or grounds for confusion.
fields.label: Caution

fields.description: Any interesting single amino-acid site on the sequence, that is not defined by another feature key. It can also apply to an amino acid bond which is represented by the positions of the two flanking amino acids.
fields.label: Site

fields.description: An experimental method.
fields.label: Method

fields.description: Different sources report differing sequences.
fields.label: Sequence Conflict

fields.description: Description of the quaternary structure of a protein.
fields.label: Subunit

fields.description: Warning about possible errors related to the protein sequence
fields.label: Sequence Caution

fields.description: Data that was submitted directly to a database.
fields.label: Submission Citation

fields.description: A range of amino acids on a protein  sequence.
fields.label: Range

fields.description: Description of the reactions catalyzed by an enzyme.
fields.label: Catalytic Activity

fields.description: An experimental method for measuring the mass of a molecule.
fields.label: Mass Measurement

fields.description: Description of an enzyme regulatory mechanism.
fields.label: Enzyme Regulation

fields.description: Extent of a zinc finger region.
fields.label: Zinc Finger

fields.description: Description of the use of a specific protein in a biotechnological process.
fields.label: Biotechnology

fields.description: Extent of a calcium-binding region.
fields.label: Calcium Binding

fields.description: General description of the functions of a protein.
fields.label: Function

fields.description: Indicates the mass of a sequence determined by mass spectrometry.
fields.label: Mass

fields.description: Covalent binding of a lipid moiety.
fields.label: Lipid Binding

fields.description: The relationship between a protein and a protein family.
fields.label: Family Membership Statement

fields.description: Description of a protein-protein interaction.
fields.label: Interaction

fields.description: Extent of a released active peptide.
fields.label: Peptide

fields.description: An element of a taxonomy for classifying life forms.
fields.label: Taxon

fields.description: Extent of a compositionally biased region.
fields.label: Compositionally Biased Region

fields.description: A concept used to classify resources.
fields.label: Concept

fields.description: Description of a publication from which data was obtained.
fields.label: Citation

fields.description: Describes amino acid modifications, post pre- and post-translational.
fields.label: Modification

fields.label: Shandy

fields.description:
The production and labeling of American whiskey are governed by Title 27 of
    the U.S. Code of Federal Regulations.
fields.label: American Whiskey

fields.description:
Dunkel is the German word meaning dark, and dunkel beers typically range in
    color from amber to dark reddish brown. They are characterized by their
    smooth malty flavor.
fields.label: Dunkel

fields.description:
Vodka is made by the distillation of fermented substances such as grains,
    potatoes, or sometimes fruits or sugar.
fields.label: Vodka

fields.description:
The yeast will ferment the beer quickly, giving it a sweet, full bodied and
    fruity taste.
fields.label: Ale

fields.description:
The name of the spirit derives from its historical association with an area
    known as Old Bourbon, around what is now Bourbon County, Kentucky (which,
    in turn, was named after the French House of Bourbon royal family). It has
    been produced since the 18th century. While it may be made anywhere in the
    United States, it is strongly associated with the American South in
    general, and Kentucky in particular.
fields.label: Bourbon Whiskey

fields.description:
It is known as the standard longneck bottle or industry standard bottle
    (ISB). The ISB longnecks have a uniform capacity, height, weight and
    diameter and can be reused on average 16 times. The long neck offers a long
    cushion of air to absorb the pressure of carbonation to reduce the risk of
    exploding. The longneck also provides a handle for drinking directly from
    the bottle without transferring body heat to the beer from one's hand.
fields.label: Longneck

fields.description: Mineral water may be sparkling due to contained gases.
fields.label: Mineral Water

fields.description:
Brandy generally contains 35–60% alcohol by volume (70–120 US proof) and is
    typically taken as an after-dinner drink. Some brandies are aged in wooden
    casks, some are colored with caramel coloring to imitate the effect of
    aging, and some brandies are produced using a combination of both aging and
    coloring.
fields.label: Brandy

fields.description:
Beverage cans are made of aluminium (75% of worldwide production) or
    tin-plated steel (25% worldwide production).
fields.label: Beverage Can

fields.description:
Glass bottles can vary in size considerably, but are most commonly found in
    sizes ranging between about 10ml and 5 litres.
fields.label: Glass Bottle

fields.description:
Some mixed drinks are alcoholic beverages that contain liquor; others are
    non-alcoholic.
fields.label: Mixed Drink

fields.description:
This excludes undistilled fermented beverages such as beer, wine, and
     cider.
fields.label: Distilled Beverage

fields.description:
The starch and saccharification enzymes are often derived from malted cereal
    grains, most commonly malted barley and malted wheat.
fields.label: Beer

fields.description:
The name came about as a result of its popularity with street and river
    porters.
fields.label: Porter

fields.description:
Plastic bottles are typically used to store liquids such as water, soft
    drinks, motor oil, cooking oil, medicine, shampoo, milk, and ink.
fields.label: Plastic Bottle

fields.description:
Liqueurs are typically quite sweet; they are usually not aged for long
    after the ingredients are mixed, but may have resting periods during their
    production to allow flavors to marry.
fields.label: Liqueur

fields.description:
Key regulations defining Irish whiskey and its production are established
    by the Irish Whiskey Act of 1980.
fields.label: Irish Whiskey

fields.description:
Stouts were traditionally the generic term for the strongest or stoutest
    porters, typically 7% or 8%, produced by a brewery.
fields.label: Stout

fields.description: It is one of the world's major beer styles.
fields.label: Pale Ale

fields.description:
Dark amber or brown glass greatly reduces UV light from spoiling the beer.
    However, lighter colored bottles are often used for marketing reasons.
fields.label: Beer Bottle

fields.description:
Cocktails were originally a mixture of spirits, sugar, water, and bitters.
    It is now often used for almost any mixed drink that contains alcohol,
    including mixers, mixed shots, etc. A cocktail today usually contains one
    or more kinds of spirit and one or more mixers, such as soda or fruit juice.
    Additional ingredients may be sugar, honey, milk, cream, and various herbs.
fields.label: Cocktail

fields.description:
The distillate, a clear liquid, is then usually aged in
    oak barrels.
fields.label: Rum

fields.description:
As with any Scotch whisky, a single malt Scotch must be distilled in
    Scotland and matured in oak casks in Scotland for at least three years
    (most single malts are matured longer).
fields.label: Single Malt Scotch

fields.description:
Its taste is comparable to vodka, though often slightly sweeter due to
    sugars added in the manufacturing process.
fields.label: Soju

Most Principal Secretaries of State are titled 'Secretary of State' – although some have traditional titles, such as the Chancellor of the Exchequer and the Chief Whip.
fields.label: Principal Secretary of State

fields.description: Cabinet is the supreme decision-making body in government, dealing with the big issues of the day and the Government’s overall strategy.

The the cardinality of days in a year is set to between 351 and 380 because in the UK the end of a business reporting year must be within 7 days of an annual reference date. In the worst cases this allows a reporting interval to be shortened or extended by up to two weeks.
fields.label: Generic Year (Class)

fields.description: A class for calendar aligned intervals that represent a calendar half year, a year being split into two half year periods of 6 months each.

fields.description: A generic superclass for all half-year (6 month) like intervals

fields.description: A class for all calendar aligned intervals.  The start of a given interval is aligned with the start of each of its first (temporally) subordinate CalendarInterval. fields.description: A generic superclass for all day like entities.

fields.description: Events are things that happen. This comprises everything from historical events to web site sessions and mythical journeys. Event is the central class of SEM.
fields.label: Event

fields.description: Places are locations where an Event happens. They do not need to be physical places and hence do not necessarily need coordinates. Neither do they need to have any significance apart from them being the location of an Event.
fields.label: Place

fields.description: Roles are properties with a subspecified function or position indicated by a RoleType in the scope of an Event. For example, the sem:hasActor property can be subspecified with the RoleType attacker, to denote that the type of participation of the Actor in the scope of the Event is "attacker". The sem:hasPlace property can be subspecified with the RoleType origin, to denote that within the scope of the Event it is the origin.
fields.label: Role

fields.description: EventType contains all resources that are used to classify Time, e.g. century.
fields.label: Time type

fields.description: Actors are entities that take part in an Event, either actively or passively. Actors do not necessarily have to be sentient. They can also be objects. Actors are a thing, animate or inanimate, physical or non-physical.
fields.label: Actor

fields.description: Time contains symbolic representations of when an Event took place. Time instances do not necessarily need to have a timestamp associated with them. The Time class exists to represent semantics of time, e.g. that one thing happens before another, even though the exact timestamps are unknown.
fields.label: Time

fields.description: EventType contains all resources that are used to classify Events, e.g. meeting.
fields.label: Event type

fields.description: Views are properties that only hold according to a certain Authority.
fields.label: View

fields.description: EventType contains all resources that are used to classify Roles, e.g. receiver.
fields.label: Role type

However, when executed, these axioms should not be executed over themselves, because we don't want the system to reason about the SPIN triples to speed up things.

fields.description: This class represents universities. We decided to introduce two different classes to distinguish between universities and independent research institutes. The main difference is actually the different kinds of independence. In contrast to a university, a research institute is independent from the rigorous bureaucracy of the mainly state-run universities. On the other hand, a university is independent from the economy and the financial support of companies. Thus, the kind of research an independent research institute practises is generally more application-oriented.

fields.description:
This class is the superclass for all classes defining geographical locations. The approach for this subontology is to have a hierarchy of location classes, such that instances of the classes further down in the hierarchy can be contained in instances of the classes higher up in the hierarchy. On each level, there exist two sister classes: class L defines a certain type of location, while class SubL defines locations which can be contained in instances of L. SubL then defines a property inL, to express which instance of L an instance of SubL is contained in. E.g. for a class Continent, there exists a class SubContinent. All children of SubContinent (either direct or transitive) define locations that can be contained in a continent, such as countries, regions, cities, etc. By virtue of inheritance, all these location classes then have a property inContinent, to express that they are contained in some continent. In a simpler, flat structure, inContinent would have to be defined explicitly for all kinds of locations that can be contained in a continent.
The intepretation of the inL predicates should be as follows: if, for a particular instance K, inL has a value, this value is valid. If inL has no value, the value of inL in the next location K is contained in valid, and so forth. E.g. an instance "Hawaii" has the value "Oceania" defined for <link>inContinent</link> and "USA" for <link>inCountry</link>. "Delaware" has no value for inContinent. "USA" has the value "North America" for <link>inContinent</link>. The interpretation would be that "Hawaii" is located in "Oceania", while "Delaware" is located in "North America".
We are aware of the fact that this approach is idealized and can therefore conflict with reality in some situations. E.g., the exact borders of continents are not always defined (there are contradicting opinions on where exactly Europe begins or ends). Countries could be contained in more than one continent (Turkey belongs to both Europe and Asia). However, we think that these situations are marginal and have little or no impact on the intended use of this ontology.
We think that this recursive modelling of locations is at the same time simple and powerful enough to capture all necessary aspects of the concept of location for a domain such as an SWPortal. While the SubL classes might appear to be somewhat artificial, they are actually not. They are just an abstraction for geographical entities that are (under normal circumstances) smaller than entities of type L. As such, they are no more abstract than, say, the concept of an agent.
fields.label: Location

fields.description: Physical feature, defined by its physical characteristics on planet Earth, including mountains, rivers, and oceans. Used in TGN only
fields.label: PhysPlaceConcept

fields.description: Top of a hierarchy. Used in AAT only. Not used for indexing or cataloguing
fields.label: Hierarchy

fields.description:
Defines a GVP subject or provides usage information. Has fields:
- dc:identifier: numeric ID, also used in the URL.
- rdf:value: the note itself (as per SKOS Primer: 4.2 Advanced Documentation Features) with language tag
- dct:language: matches the language tag
- gvp:displayOrder, order of this note amongst others
- gvp:historicFlag, schema:startDate, schema:endDate, rdfs:comment: Historic Information about applicability
- dct:source or subproperties thereof 
- dct:contributor or subproperties thereof
fields.label: Scope Note

fields.description:
Node in a GVP vocabulary hierarchy. 
May be Facet, GuideTerm, Hierarchy, Concept, AdminPlaceConcept, PhysPlaceConcept, PhysAdminPlaceConcept, or ObsoleteSubject.
Implemented as skos:Concept or iso:ThesaurusArray and skos:Collection

fields.description: Place that is both administrative and physical. Rarely used. Used in TGN only
fields.label: PhysAdminPlaceConcept

fields.description: Obsolete subject: moved out of the publishable hierarchy, or merged to another (pointed by dct:isReplacedBy)
fields.label: ObsoleteSubject

fields.description: Place defined by administrative boundaries and conditions, including inhabited places, nations, and empires. Used in TGN only
fields.label: AdminPlaceConcept

fields.description: Proper concept. Used in AAT only (TGN has its gvp:AdminPlaceConcept and two more). Used for indexing and cataloguing
fields.label: Concept

fields.description: One of the major divisions of a vocabulary
fields.label: Facet

fields.description: Guide Term: place holder to create a level in the hierarchy. Used in AAT only. Not used for indexing or cataloguing.
fields.label: GuideTerm

fields.description: Et fylke er et område som utgjør en førsteordens politisk og administrativ enhet.
fields.label: Fylke

fields.label: Service Stop

fields.description: A public transport service that operates a route on a given schedule.
fields.label: Service

fields.description: A location where passengers board or disembark from a transit vehicle for a specific route.
fields.label: Route Stop

fields.description: A public transportation route utilising buses on roads for short- or long-distance travel.
fields.label: Bus Route

fields.description: A service that travels in an outbound direction.

fields.description: A transfer point between two routes where the departing vehicle is expected to wait for the arriving one with sufficient time for a passenger to transfer between routes.
fields.label: Timed Transfer

fields.description: A public transportation route utilising street-level cable cars where the cable runs beneath the car.
fields.label: Cable Car Route

fields.description: A public transportation route utilising a rail system for intercity or long-distance travel.
fields.label: Rail Route

fields.description: A transfer point between two routes.
fields.label: Transfer

fields.description: A public transportation route.

fields.description: A type of arrangement for picking up or dropping off passengers from a service stop.

fields.description: A service that travels in an inbound direction.

fields.description: An organization that oversees public transportation for a city or region.

fields.description: A public transportation route utilising aerial cable cars where the car is suspended from the cable.
fields.label: Gondala Route

fields.description: A physical structure or area that contains one or more stops.

fields.description: A class of fare payable for public transportation.
fields.label: Fare

fields.description: A public transportation route utilising light rail or street level railed vehicles within a metropolitan area.
fields.label: Tram Route

fields.description: A public transportation route utilising a rail system designed for steep inclines.
fields.label: Funicular Route

fields.description: A public transport schedule that applies for one or more routes.
fields.label: Schedule

fields.description: A location where passengers board or disembark from a transit vehicle.
fields.label: Transit Stop

fields.description: A public transportation route utilising an underground rail system within a metropolitan area.
fields.label: Subway Route

fields.description: A transfer point between two routes that requires a minimum amount of time between arrival and departure to ensure a connection.
fields.label: Minimum Time Transfer

fields.description: A point that is recommended for transfer between two routes.
fields.label: Timed Transfer

fields.description: A point where transfer between two routes is not possible despite appearing possible by proximity.
fields.label: Unavailable Transfer

fields.description: A public transportation route utilising boats for short- or long-distance travel.
fields.label: Ferry Route

fields.description: The classification of the incident
fields.label: Classification

fields.description: A Unit which can be send to a incident
fields.label: Unit

fields.description: Resources of this class describe messages sent by a dispatch to individual units
fields.label: DispatchMessage

fields.description: A set of service encoding schemes and/or formats
fields.label: Service Class

fields.description: A set of function encoding schemes and/or formats
fields.label: Function Class

fields.description: A set of document encoding schemes and/or formats
fields.label: Document Class

fields.description: The set of audience types specified by the AGLS Audience Scheme.
fields.label: AGLS Audience Vocabulary

fields.description: A set of availability encoding schemes and/or formats

fields.description: A set of agent encoding schemes and/or formats
fields.label: AGLS Agent Class

fields.description: A set of jurisdiction encoding schemes and/or formats
fields.label: Jurisdiction Class

fields.description: An organization which has a political connotation
fields.label: Political Organization

fields.description: Any kind of recorded video, which is tangible.  This also includes a mpeg file on a machine
fields.label: Recorded-Video

fields.description: A generalized transfer in which information is passed from main agent to one or more recipient agents.  Examples include giving a tutorial.
fields.label: Information-Transfer-Event

fields.description: Merrian-Webster has a good set of definitions for a method. They say it is 'a systematic procedure, technique, or mode of inquiry employed by or proper to a particular discipline or art;  a systematic plan followed in presenting material for instruction; a way, technique, or process of or for doing something; a body of skills or techniques'. This is very much also what we mean by method.
fields.label: Method

fields.description: A publication which contains items which cane be themselves referenced through a publication reference.  Composite publications include newspapers, magazines and journals. A book which is a collection of articles is a composite publication, a monograph is not
fields.label: Composite-Publication

fields.description: a generalized transfer in which information is passed from main agent to one or more recipient agents.  examples include giving a tutorial.
fields.label: Sending-An-Email

fields.description: When something is produced
fields.label: Event-Involving-Production

fields.description: we have decided that a publication reference is an intangible, abstract information
fields.label: Publication-Reference

fields.description: This is a minimalist definition of class event.  We start with the very basic and we will then add slots as we specialise this definition for specific classes of events. The fillers of slots has-other-agents-involved and has-main-agent should not intersect
fields.label: Event

fields.description: This notion comes from Cyc.  It is useful to group together all information bearing entities, including video, audio and documents. An information bearing object may have an author (a generic agent) and may be owned by a legal agent. It is a tangible object
fields.label: Information-Bearing-Object

fields.description: Something tangible designed to transport people, animals, objects from A to B. For instance a bycicle, a car, a boat, etc.
fields.label: Transportation-Device

fields.description: Any kind of recorded audio, which is tangible.  This also includes a audio file on a machine
fields.label: Recorded-Audio

fields.description: A publication is something which has one or more publication references. A publication can be both an article in a journal or a journal itself. The distinction between publication and publication-reference makes it possible to distinguish between multiple occurrences of the sam publication, for instance in different media
fields.label: Publication

fields.description: A generic class to specify generic areas for research or business initiatives. For instance, the area in which a project is situated
fields.label: Generic-Area-Of-Interest

fields.description: A person which has an affiliation with some organization. For instance employees are affiliated to the organization they work for, students to the institution where they are studying, etc. A person can have multiple affiliations, which means that there is no constraint relating the values of slot has-affiliation-to-unit to the values of slot has-affiliation
fields.label: Affiliated-Person

fields.description: Information in general, independent of an object in which it is encoded. Whatever is transferred in an information-transfer event. It is clearly an intangible thing
fields.label: Abstract-Information

fields.description: A geopolitical entity is a geographical area which is associated with some sort of political structure. For instance, Russia, Italy, The-city-of-Messina, etc. A geopolitical entity can be also seen as an agent - e.g., France declared war to Spain
fields.label: Geopolitical-Entity

fields.description: Some agents have legal status: definitely organizations and people, anybody else?
fields.label: Legal Agent

fields.description: By technology we mean engineered applications of science. I guess we are probably confining ourselves to tangible things but as I am not sure I will use thing as the direct superclass - e.g., an algorithm is an intangible thing, but it could be seen as a technology, if we give a broad interpretation of the term
fields.label: Technology

fields.description: Legal agents can be either organizations or people. An awarding body is normally an organization, an individual, or a bunch of people
fields.label: Awarding-Body

fields.description: HPKB says that genders are intangible..Uhm...
fields.label: Gender

fields.description: An organization is a type of legal agent
fields.label: Organization

fields.description: An award is an intangible thing, even if the piece of paper which is often associated with an award is tangible.  What about the virtual piece of paper in the virtual degree ceremony?  I guess that ought to be an intangible
fields.label: Award

fields.description: This comes from the ontolingua library. A periodical-publication is published regularly, such as once every week.  Strictly speaking, the noun 'periodical' is used by librarians to refer to things published at intervals of greater than a day.  We use the phase periodical-publication to include newspapers and other daily publications, since they share many bibliographic features. The periodicity indicates how often the publication comes out. Note that this is a duration, rather than a time interval. A time interval indicates a specific time interval on the time continuum, so we need to model periodicity as a time quantity
fields.label: Periodical-Publication

fields.description: This is a generic notion, an agent can be an organization, a person an animal, a software agent, etc
fields.label: Generic Agent

fields.description: A generic class for addresses, whether email or postal. We see an address as abstract information and therefore it is an intangible thing
fields.label: Address

fields.description: This is an event in which the main agent (plus maybe others) goes from some place to another
fields.label: Event-Involving-Movement

fields.description: A meeting type of event. Note that both attendee and organizer have multiple cardinality
fields.label: Meeting-Taking-Place

fields.description: SME are important, so we define a class to represent them explicitly. In some case we might not know or we do not want to bother specifying excatly whether something is a small-organization or a medium-organization. Hence, we can just say 'x is a SME' without going into further detail.
fields.label: Small or Medium-sized Organization

fields.description: We use EU guidelines to distinguish between different organization sizes
fields.label: Organization Size

fields.description: A partnership is not necessarily a company, e.g. a consultancy firm is not a company
fields.label: Partnership

fields.description: This used to be called periodical publication.  However, many periodicals do not appear at fixed intervals, which is why librarians refer to them as serials. So, we now use the concept of serial publication and the has-periodicity slot has been removed
fields.label: Serial-Publication

fields.description: A degree is type of award
fields.label: Degree

fields.description: An event in which the main agent transfers something (the thing-acted-on, tangible or intangible) to one or more recipient agents. Note that we do not say anything about whether the original agent still retain the thing-acted-on.  In some cases this is clearly true ('I pass my wisdom on to my daughter'), in other cases it is not (I give you my wallet).
fields.label: Generalized-Transfer

fields.description: This is a generic class to catch all sorts of borderline and metaphorical ways to carry things from A to B
fields.label: Generalised-Means-Of-Transport

fields.description: A web browser is not a web-based system!
fields.label: Web-Browser

fields.description: 'Real' geographical regions
fields.label: Geographical-Region

fields.description: Modified to allow addresses to be given as strings, with no structure
fields.label: Postal-Address

fields.description: A system which is accessible through the web
fields.label: Web-Based-System

fields.description: A generic class for locations.  It includes both real and fantastic places
fields.label: Location

fields.description: An organization may have a number of units. Units may themselves have sub-units
fields.label: Organization-Unit

fields.description: From SUO: Any specification of how many or how much of something there is. Accordingly, there are two subclasses of Quantity: Number (how many) and Physical-Quantity (how much).
fields.label: Quantity

fields.description: An interval is defined by two time points or a duration. Classes of intervals, e.g., a day, can be defined by specifying only a duration.  A time interval has no gaps
fields.label: Time Interval

fields.description: A time position is either a time interval or a time point. Any time position is relative to a time zone
fields.label: Time Position

fields.description: The class of all unit of measures used to measure time, e.g., minute, second, hour, etc.
fields.label: Time Measure

fields.description: SUO: Physical Quantities are distinguished from Numbers by the fact that the former are associated with a dimension of measurement.
fields.label: Physical Quantity

fields.description: A measure of time, e.g., 5 hours
fields.label: Duration

fields.description: Something which is not intangible, something which is physical, made of matter. It does not matter whether things are real of imaginary.  Therefore we consider Mickey Mouse's car and a hippogriff as  tangible things
fields.label: Tangible Thing

fields.description: This comes from HPKB upper level. The collection of things that are not physical - are not made of, or encoded in, matter. Every Collection is an Intangible (even if its instances are tangible), and so are some Individuals. Caution: do not confuse `tangibility' with `perceivability' - humans can perceive light even though it's intangible - at least in a sense.
fields.label: Intangible Thing

fields.description: A point in time
fields.label: Calendar Date

fields.description: Like in Cyc, this is something which has a temporal extent.
fields.label: Temporal Thing

fields.description: Any kind of unit of measure, metre, dollar, kilogram, etc.
fields.label: Unit of Measure

fields.description: This is the top-level concept in the AKT reference ontology
fields.label: Thing

fields.description: A point in time
fields.label: Time Point

fields.description: A web document is a page available from a content-negotiable URL on the BBC website or any web document to which the BBC points at.
fields.label: WebDocument

fields.description: Class representing the different products creating content. Within the BBC's scope, this would be one of the ten Future Media Products. Outside the BBC, this could refer to an organisation or company whose web pages we link to. Typically the official web pages of things or their Wikipedia, Twitter and Facebook.
fields.label: Product

fields.description: This class is needed to support the different categories of web documents. This is meant to be extended by the clients with categories of web documents that make sense to their own product. For example, dynamically generated aggregations of content or editorially curated profiles of things.
fields.label: WebDocumentCategory

fields.description: Represents the different types of platforms through which a web document can be accessed. This is needed to derive the correct web document for consumption from the appropriate platform. If there's no specification on platform suitability then the document is considered to be suitable for both

fields.description: This class represents all identifiers required for locating a representation of the thing in another BBC system. Thing locators usially follow the pattern<urn:LocatorType:localID> for example <urn:sports-stats:11269354> or <urn:cps:7f0da524-08bd-4d7e-848e-f50ccca6d87c> (see the class LocatorType for available locator types) where the last fragment of the uri is the native id of the system.

fields.description: This locator is used to create locators for the sports-data system

fields.description: This locator is used to create locators for the sports-stats system
fields.label: Sports-StatsLocator

fields.description: This is needed to instantiate locators used by the Location Services Ingestion system
fields.label: LocationServicesLocator

fields.description: This locator type is used for creating locators for PIPS, the system that manages the Programmes Information Pages.
fields.label: PipsLocator

fields.description: This types is needed to instantiate locators used by the Music bootstrap service
fields.label: MusicBootstrapLocator

fields.description: This is the class of systems that manage data in the Linked Data Platform.todo
fields.label: System

fields.description: This locator type is used for creating locators for the Content Publishing System which is largely used to create the News and Sport stories on the website.
fields.label: CPSLocator

fields.description: This locator is used to create locators for Pulsar TODO
fields.label: PulsarLocator

fields.description: This class of locators is used to retrieve things through the Content API

fields.description: The class of places in the BBC.

fields.description: The superclass of all things the BBC creates or talks about
fields.label: Thing

fields.description: The class of people in the BBC. Subclasses of this can be all types of people such as politicians, athletes, historic figures, contributors in programmes e.t.c.
fields.label: Person

fields.description: The class of events in the BBC. This is a generic class to represent events (music events, historic events, sports events, politics events, e.t.c.)

fields.description: The class of all news items that the BBC produces. They can be textual articles, or media asset pages (audio or video) or live coverage of events (use the liveCoverage property).

fields.description: This is the class of creative works that are associated with particular journalists or correspondents. The analysis, commentary and personal viewpoint of the creator is reflected on the blog post and the blog post is usually associated prominently with the name of the creator. BlogPost can be have liveCoverage or not and different types of formats

fields.description: Used to associate a Creative Work with the canonical location of the thumbnail. The URI of each of its instances is the full canonical location of the thumbnail
fields.label: Thumbnail

fields.description: The Episodes subclass of programmes produced by the BBC
fields.label: Episode

fields.description: Enumerated class of the audiences
fields.label: Audience

fields.description: The class of programmes produced by the BBC

For the other differentiations of types of content we have the primaryFormat, liveCoverage and category properties)

fields.description: Enumerated class of the allowed thumbnail types

fields.description: This class is used to decribe that creative works which are coverage of a live event. (Note that this isn't meant to describe the fact that the event is live currently. An example of a Live Coverage creative work is the live event page covering live the England VS Australia cricket match, last saturday's football matches or last year's elections)
